// notes/ml.js — TOPIC_CONTENT entries for the ml phase
Object.assign(TOPIC_CONTENT, {
  "ml_intro": "<main>\n  <h1>ML Basics</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">What ML actually is</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">A function learned from data, not programmed</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Types of ML</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Supervised, unsupervised, semi-supervised, self-supervised</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The ML lifecycle</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Problem \u2192 data \u2192 features \u2192 train \u2192 evaluate \u2192 deploy \u2192 monitor</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Supervised learning setup</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Features, labels, train/val/test split</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The generalisation problem</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why training performance \u2260 production performance</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Data leakage</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The silent killer \u2014 how to spot and prevent it</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>What ML actually is:</strong> a system that learns a function f(X) \u2192 y from data rather than having f explicitly programmed. At training time you show (X, y) examples. At inference time you apply f to new X the model has never seen. The entire challenge is generalisation \u2014 learning f that works on new data, not just the training examples.</li>\n    <li><strong>Supervised vs self-supervised:</strong> supervised requires human-labelled (X, y) pairs \u2014 expensive. Self-supervised derives labels from the data itself: predict the next word from previous words (GPT), fill in a masked token (BERT). This is how LLMs scale \u2014 billions of examples with zero human annotation cost. Semi-supervised sits between: small labelled set + large unlabelled set, using the unlabelled data to improve representations.</li>\n    <li><strong>The lifecycle bottleneck:</strong> most teams invest in model training (stages 4-6) and underinvest in deployment and monitoring (stages 7-8). A model that performs well in development and silently degrades in production is worse than a weaker model with good monitoring \u2014 at least the latter fails visibly. Distribution shift, concept drift, and upstream data pipeline failures are invisible without monitoring.</li>\n    <li><strong>Data leakage \u2014 the silent killer:</strong> fitting a scaler on the full dataset before splitting leaks test statistics into training. Using features computed after the event you're predicting (future information). Target encoding without cross-validation \u2014 the category mean encodes the label. All produce optimistically biased scores that collapse in production. Fix: Pipeline enforces fit-on-train-only automatically.</li>\n    <li><strong>Baseline first, always:</strong> the correct sequence is: mean predictor \u2192 logistic regression / linear regression \u2192 gradient boosting. If a mean predictor gives you 85% accuracy, you need to understand why before adding complexity. Feature engineering matters more than algorithm choice \u2014 a simple model with good features beats a complex model with bad ones.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. WHAT ML IS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-what\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>What ML actually is</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Machine Learning</span>\n    <p>Machine learning is the practice of building systems that learn a mapping from inputs X to outputs y from data, rather than having that mapping explicitly programmed. Given examples (X, y), a learning algorithm finds a function f such that f(X) \u2248 y. At inference time, f is applied to new inputs the algorithm has never seen.</p>\n    <p>The key word is <strong>generalise</strong>. A model that perfectly memorises training examples but fails on new ones has learned nothing useful. The entire field is about finding functions that generalise \u2014 that capture the true underlying pattern rather than the noise in the training data.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 a doctor who learns from cases, not a rulebook</span>\n    <p>A traditional rule-based system is a doctor given an explicit rulebook: \"if temperature &gt; 38.5\u00b0C AND WBC &gt; 11,000, diagnose infection.\" The rules work for the cases the rulebook author anticipated. A new symptom combination: the rulebook is silent.<br><br>\n    An ML system is a doctor who learns from thousands of patient cases and outcomes. They develop an intuition for patterns the rulebook never captured. They generalise to new presentations because they've learned the underlying biology, not just the rules. The risk: if the training cases were biased or incomplete, the intuition is wrong in systematic ways \u2014 and it's hard to know which ways.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. TYPES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-types\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Types of Machine Learning</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the four paradigms</span>\n    <p><strong>Supervised learning:</strong> every training example has a label y. The model learns f(X) \u2192 y by comparing predictions against known answers. Two subtypes: regression (y \u2208 \u211d, continuous output) and classification (y \u2208 finite set of categories).<br><br>\n    <strong>Unsupervised learning:</strong> no labels. The algorithm finds structure in X alone \u2014 groupings (clustering), compressed representations (dimensionality reduction), density estimates, or anomalies.<br><br>\n    <strong>Semi-supervised learning:</strong> a small labelled set plus a large unlabelled set. The labelled set guides the model; the unlabelled set helps it learn better representations of the input space. Common in NLP and computer vision where annotation is expensive.<br><br>\n    <strong>Self-supervised learning:</strong> labels are generated from the data itself without human annotation. Predict the next word from the previous words (GPT). Predict a masked token (BERT). Predict a missing image patch. The model learns rich representations without any human labels \u2014 this is what makes LLMs possible at scale.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Paradigm</th><th>Labels?</th><th>Goal</th><th>Examples</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Supervised \u2014 Regression</td><td>Yes (continuous)</td><td>Predict a number</td><td>Demand forecasting, house prices, salary prediction</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Supervised \u2014 Classification</td><td>Yes (categorical)</td><td>Predict a category</td><td>Fraud detection, spam filter, image classification</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Unsupervised \u2014 Clustering</td><td>No</td><td>Find groups</td><td>Customer segmentation, anomaly detection</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Unsupervised \u2014 Dim. Reduction</td><td>No</td><td>Compress features</td><td>PCA for visualisation, feature extraction</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Semi-supervised</td><td>Few</td><td>Learn from limited labels</td><td>Text classification with 100 labelled + 100K unlabelled</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Self-supervised</td><td>Auto-generated</td><td>Learn representations</td><td>GPT (next word), BERT (masked word), SimCLR (contrastive)</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. LIFECYCLE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-lifecycle\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>The ML Lifecycle</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the 8 stages, in order</span>\n    <p>Most ML failures happen at stage 1 (wrong problem definition) or stages 7-8 (deployment and monitoring). The model-building stages 4-6 get 90% of the attention in courses and 40% of the time in real projects.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Stage by stage \u2014 what actually matters at each step</span>\n    <p><strong>1. Problem definition.</strong> What decision will this model inform? What is the cost of a false positive vs false negative? What metric matters to the business (not just to you)? Getting this wrong means building a model nobody uses or that optimises the wrong thing.<br><br>\n    <strong>2. Data collection &amp; understanding.</strong> Where does the data come from? Is it representative of production? What time period? EDA: distributions, missing values, outliers, class balance, temporal patterns. Garbage in \u2192 garbage out, no exceptions.<br><br>\n    <strong>3. Feature engineering.</strong> Transform raw data into features the model can use. This is the highest-leverage step \u2014 better features improve any model. Feature engineering skill is what separates good ML engineers from people who just run sklearn.<br><br>\n    <strong>4. Data splitting.</strong> Train / validation / test. Test set is locked and touched exactly once. If you evaluate on test multiple times and pick the model that does best, you've turned it into a validation set.<br><br>\n    <strong>5. Baseline model.</strong> Always. Fit the simplest model first \u2014 mean predictor, linear regression, logistic regression, single decision tree. Know what you're beating before investing in complexity.<br><br>\n    <strong>6. Model selection and tuning.</strong> Compare models using cross-validation. Tune the winner. Report unbiased performance on the test set once.<br><br>\n    <strong>7. Deployment.</strong> Wrap in an API, container, or pipeline. Monitor inference latency. Handle missing features gracefully. Version the model. This is where most academic ML education ends and real engineering begins.<br><br>\n    <strong>8. Monitoring.</strong> Models decay. The distribution of inputs in production drifts from training. Label distribution shifts. Feature pipelines break silently. Without monitoring, you won't know the model is wrong until a human notices.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 90\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <defs><marker id=\"arr\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\"/></marker></defs>\n      <!-- stages -->\n      <g text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\">\n        <rect x=\"5\"   y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--blue-dim)\"   stroke=\"var(--border-s)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"41\"  y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">Problem</text>\n        <rect x=\"87\"  y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--teal-dim)\"   stroke=\"rgba(8,145,178,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"123\" y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--teal)\">Data / EDA</text>\n        <rect x=\"169\" y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--violet-dim)\" stroke=\"rgba(124,58,237,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"205\" y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--violet)\">Features</text>\n        <rect x=\"251\" y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--blue-dim)\"   stroke=\"var(--border-s)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"287\" y=\"44\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">Train /</text>\n        <text x=\"287\" y=\"55\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">Evaluate</text>\n        <rect x=\"333\" y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--amber-dim)\"  stroke=\"rgba(180,83,9,.2)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"369\" y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">Test set</text>\n        <rect x=\"415\" y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\"  stroke=\"rgba(5,150,105,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"451\" y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Deploy</text>\n        <rect x=\"497\" y=\"28\" width=\"72\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--red-dim)\"    stroke=\"rgba(220,38,38,.25)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"533\" y=\"47\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Monitor</text>\n        <rect x=\"579\" y=\"28\" width=\"112\" height=\"32\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"var(--s2)\" stroke=\"var(--border)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n        <text x=\"635\" y=\"44\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Retrain /</text>\n        <text x=\"635\" y=\"55\" font-weight=\"600\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Improve</text>\n      </g>\n      <!-- arrows -->\n      <path d=\"M77 44 L87 44\"   stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M159 44 L169 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M241 44 L251 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M323 44 L333 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M405 44 L415 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M487 44 L497 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M569 44 L579 44\" stroke=\"var(--ink3)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <!-- feedback loop arrow -->\n      <path d=\"M691 60 Q 691 82 41 82 L 41 60\" stroke=\"var(--blue)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 3\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arr)\"/>\n      <text x=\"370\" y=\"77\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"var(--blue)\">monitoring triggers retraining \u2192 cycle repeats</text>\n    </svg>\n    <figcaption>The lifecycle is a loop, not a pipeline. Deploy is not the end \u2014 monitoring feeds back into problem refinement and retraining.</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. SUPERVISED SETUP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-setup\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Supervised Learning Setup</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 features, labels, splits</span>\n    <p><strong>Features (X):</strong> the input variables the model receives. Can be numerical, categorical, text, image, time-series. Feature quality is the largest determinant of model performance.<br><br>\n    <strong>Label (y):</strong> the target you're trying to predict. For regression: a continuous value. For classification: a discrete class. The label must be available at training time but not at inference time \u2014 otherwise you're leaking the answer.<br><br>\n    <strong>Train / Validation / Test split:</strong> Train (60-80%) \u2014 the model sees this and learns from it. Validation (10-20%) \u2014 used for model selection and hyperparameter tuning. Evaluated multiple times. Test (10-20%) \u2014 locked. Evaluated exactly once at the very end. If you evaluate on test more than once and pick based on results, it becomes a second validation set and your reported performance is optimistic.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> train_test_split\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pandas <span class=\"k\">as</span> pd\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Standard split</span>\nX_trainval, X_test, y_trainval, y_test = train_test_split(\n    X, y, test_size=<span class=\"y\">0.15</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\nX_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(\n    X_trainval, y_trainval, test_size=<span class=\"y\">0.15</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># For time series: NEVER shuffle \u2014 use temporal ordering</span>\nn = len(X)\ntrain_end = int(n * <span class=\"y\">0.70</span>)\nval_end   = int(n * <span class=\"y\">0.85</span>)\n\nX_train = X.iloc[:train_end]\nX_val   = X.iloc[train_end:val_end]\nX_test  = X.iloc[val_end:]          <span class=\"c\"># always the most recent period</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. GENERALISATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-gen\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>The Generalisation Problem</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 why training performance \u2260 production performance</span>\n    <p>A model generalises when it performs well on data it was not trained on. Generalisation fails for several reasons: the model memorised training noise (overfitting), the training distribution doesn't match the deployment distribution (distribution shift), or the model learned a spurious correlation that happens to work on training data but breaks on new data.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Distribution shift \u2014 the most common production failure</span>\n    <p>Your model trains on last year's data. The world changes. The distribution of inputs shifts. The model's learned function f is now mapping from a distribution it was never trained on. Performance degrades \u2014 silently, if you have no monitoring.<br><br>\n    Types: <strong>Covariate shift</strong> \u2014 P(X) changes, P(y|X) stays same (users' devices change but click behaviour for a given device is same). <strong>Label shift</strong> \u2014 P(y) changes (new fraud patterns emerge). <strong>Concept drift</strong> \u2014 P(y|X) changes (the relationship between features and target has fundamentally changed). Concept drift is the most dangerous because it invalidates the model's core learned mapping, not just the distribution of inputs.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. DATA LEAKAGE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-leakage\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Data Leakage</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 leakage and why it's catastrophic</span>\n    <p>Data leakage occurs when information that would not be available at prediction time is included in the training features. The model learns to rely on this information, producing unrealistically good training and validation scores. In production, the information is absent \u2014 performance collapses. Leakage produces the most dangerous outcome in ML: confident models that are confidently wrong.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Five common leakage patterns \u2014 memorise these</span>\n    <p><strong>1. Scaling on full dataset:</strong> fitting StandardScaler on all data before splitting means training data statistics incorporate test set information. Always fit scaler on training fold only. Use sklearn Pipeline \u2014 it handles this automatically.<br><br>\n    <strong>2. Future features in time-series:</strong> using today's actual temperature to predict yesterday's demand. In production you only have a forecast. Use only information available at prediction time.<br><br>\n    <strong>3. Target encoding without CV:</strong> replacing a categorical with the mean target for that category, computed on the full training set. Rows with rare categories get their own target value effectively \u2014 the feature encodes the label. Always compute target encoding within CV folds, not on the full dataset.<br><br>\n    <strong>4. Post-event features:</strong> a feature computed after the event you're predicting. \"Was the customer's next purchase within 7 days?\" as a feature to predict churn \u2014 you only know this after the churn window closes.<br><br>\n    <strong>5. ID-correlated features:</strong> row IDs, timestamps, or file names that happen to correlate with the target in training data but not in production. The model learns \"row ID 10000-20000 tends to be positive\" \u2014 useless in deployment.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 Q&A \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-qa\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between supervised, unsupervised, and self-supervised learning?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Supervised: labelled (X, y) pairs. Model learns f(X) \u2192 y by comparing predictions to known answers. Two subtypes: regression (y continuous) and classification (y categorical). Unsupervised: no labels. Model finds structure in X \u2014 clusters (KMeans, DBSCAN), compressed representations (PCA), density estimates, or anomalies. Goal is understanding the distribution of X, not predicting y. Self-supervised: labels are automatically derived from the data itself without human annotation. Predict the next word from previous words (GPT) or fill in a masked token (BERT). The model trains on enormous unlabelled datasets and learns rich representations. This is what makes LLMs possible \u2014 human annotation would be impractical at the scale required.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why is the test set touched only once?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The test set simulates data you will encounter in production \u2014 data the model has never seen and that hasn't influenced any decisions. If you evaluate on it, see the score, adjust your model, and evaluate again, you have implicitly used test set performance to guide model development. The set is no longer held out \u2014 it's a second validation set. The score you report after multiple evaluations is optimistic: you've overfit to the test set through the model selection process. A properly held-out test set gives you an unbiased estimate of generalisation performance. You only get one shot at an unbiased estimate, and you shouldn't use it until you're done building.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is data leakage and give two examples?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Leakage is when information not available at prediction time is included in training features. It produces unrealistically good training scores and models that fail catastrophically in production. Two examples: (1) Scaling on the full dataset \u2014 fitting StandardScaler on all data before splitting means the scaler's mean and std incorporate test set statistics. The model has seen summaries of test data during training. Fix: always fit the scaler on the training fold only, using a Pipeline. (2) Future features in time series \u2014 using the actual weather temperature of day T to predict day T's demand, when in production you only have a weather forecast. The model learns to rely on ground-truth temperature that won't exist at inference time. Fix: only use features that are available at the time the prediction is made.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is concept drift and how do you handle it?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Concept drift is when P(y|X) changes \u2014 the relationship between features and the target shifts, not just the distribution of inputs. Example: a fraud model trained pre-2020. During COVID, consumer purchasing patterns changed fundamentally. The model's learned relationship between transaction features and fraud probability is now wrong \u2014 not because inputs look different (covariate shift) but because the underlying mapping has changed. Detection: monitor model performance metrics (AUC-ROC, precision at threshold) on recent data with a sliding window. A drop signals drift. PSI (Population Stability Index) on features detects covariate shift. Response: retrain on recent data, potentially with a time-weighted loss that downweights old samples. For gradual drift: scheduled retraining on a rolling window. For sudden drift: trigger retraining when monitoring detects a performance drop beyond a threshold.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_core": "<main>\n  <h1>ML Core Concepts</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Bias-Variance Tradeoff</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The decomposition \u2014 with the math</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Loss Functions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">MSE, MAE, MAPE, cross-entropy \u2014 which and why</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Gradient Descent</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Variants, momentum, Adam \u2014 the math</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Regularisation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">L1 vs L2 \u2014 the geometric intuition</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Cross-Validation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">K-fold, stratified, time-series, nested CV</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Feature Scaling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Which scaler, when it matters, leakage trap</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Bias-variance decomposition:</strong> E[(y\u2212f\u0302)\u00b2] = Bias\u00b2[f\u0302] + Var[f\u0302] + \u03c3\u00b2. Bias = E[f\u0302(x)] \u2212 f(x) \u2014 how far the average prediction across all possible training sets is from the true function. A linear model fit to quadratic data has high bias regardless of data size. Variance = how much predictions change when you train on different datasets of the same size. \u03c3\u00b2 is irreducible noise. Diagnosis: high train error = bias. Large train-val gap = variance. Different problems need different fixes.</li>\n    <li><strong>L1 vs L2 \u2014 the geometric argument:</strong> L2 (Ridge) constrains weights to an L2 ball (sphere). The loss contour first touches the sphere at a smooth curved point \u2014 weights shrink toward zero but never reach it. L1 (Lasso) constrains to an L1 ball (diamond). The diamond has corners exactly on the axes. Loss contours frequently first intersect the diamond at these corners \u2014 where one or more weights are exactly zero. L1 produces sparsity because of the shape of the constraint region, not the size of the penalty.</li>\n    <li><strong>Cross-validation leakage trap:</strong> running GridSearchCV to tune hyperparameters and then reporting that CV score is biased \u2014 the validation folds influenced which hyperparameters you picked, so they're no longer truly held out. Fix: nested CV (outer loop evaluates, inner loop tunes) or a genuinely untouched test set. TimeSeriesSplit enforces temporal ordering \u2014 standard K-fold on time series leaks the future into training.</li>\n    <li><strong>Adam vs SGD:</strong> Adam maintains first moment (momentum) and second moment (RMSProp) \u2014 adapts learning rate per parameter. Converges faster but to sharper minima. SGD with momentum is noisier, which acts as implicit regularisation and finds flatter, more generalisable minima. For tabular ML (XGBoost, LightGBM) Adam is irrelevant \u2014 they use second-order gradients internally. For neural nets: Adam for fast experimentation, SGD for squeezing final accuracy.</li>\n    <li><strong>Feature scaling trap:</strong> fitting the scaler on the full dataset leaks test statistics into training. Always use Pipeline so the scaler fits only on the training fold within each CV fold. Tree-based models need no scaling \u2014 splits are on thresholds and are invariant to monotone transformations.</li>\n    <li><strong>MAPE near zero:</strong> MAPE = |y\u2212\u0177|/|y| \u00d7 100 explodes when y approaches zero. One interval with y=0.5 and \u0177=1.0 gives MAPE=100% \u2014 a single outlier dominates the entire metric. Fix: sMAPE = 2|y\u2212\u0177|/(|y|+|\u0177|) \u00d7 100 (bounded [0,200]), or mask values below a documented threshold.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. BIAS-VARIANCE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-bv\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Bias-Variance Tradeoff</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The mathematical decomposition</span>\n    <p>For model f\u0302 trained on dataset D, predicting y = f(x) + \u03b5 (irreducible noise with variance \u03c3\u00b2):<br><br>\n    <strong>E[(y \u2212 f\u0302(x))\u00b2] = Bias[f\u0302(x)]\u00b2 + Var[f\u0302(x)] + \u03c3\u00b2</strong><br><br>\n    <strong>Bias[f\u0302(x)] = E[f\u0302(x)] \u2212 f(x)</strong> \u2014 how far the average prediction (over all possible training sets of size n) is from the true function. Systematic error. Present even with infinite data.<br><br>\n    <strong>Var[f\u0302(x)] = E[(f\u0302(x) \u2212 E[f\u0302(x)])\u00b2]</strong> \u2014 how much the prediction changes when trained on different datasets of the same size. Sensitivity to noise in the training set.<br><br>\n    \u03c3\u00b2 is irreducible \u2014 inherent noise in the data generating process. No model eliminates it.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 archery targets</span>\n    <p>High bias, low variance: every arrow clusters tightly together but far from the bullseye \u2014 consistently wrong in the same direction. High variance, low bias: arrows are centred on the bullseye on average, but scattered \u2014 unpredictable per shot. The goal: tight cluster on the bullseye.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 180\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"17\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">Diagnosing bias vs variance from train/val errors</text>\n      <rect x=\"12\"  y=\"27\" width=\"210\" height=\"145\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red-dim)\"   stroke=\"var(--red)\"   stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--red)\">High Bias \u2014 Underfitting</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Gap is small \u2014 both are bad</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Fix: more complexity, more</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"133\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">features, less regularisation</text>\n      <rect x=\"245\" y=\"27\" width=\"210\" height=\"145\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Sweet Spot</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: LOW</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: LOW and \u2248 train</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Small gap, both errors low</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Ship it.</text>\n      <rect x=\"478\" y=\"27\" width=\"210\" height=\"145\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--amber)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">High Variance \u2014 Overfitting</text>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: LOW</text>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Large gap \u2014 memorised train</text>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">Fix: more data, regularisation,</text>\n      <text x=\"583\" y=\"133\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">simpler model, early stopping</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. LOSS FUNCTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-loss\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Loss Functions</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 what you're actually optimising</span>\n    <p>A loss function maps (prediction \u0177, truth y) \u2192 scalar. Training minimises average loss across all training examples. The choice encodes your assumptions about the error distribution and what kinds of mistakes matter most. Mismatching the loss to the problem structure produces suboptimal models even with a perfect architecture.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Loss</th><th>Formula</th><th>Outlier sensitivity</th><th>Use when</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>MSE</td><td>mean((y\u2212\u0177)\u00b2)</td><td>High \u2014 squares errors</td><td>Large errors disproportionately costly. Gaussian noise assumption. Differentiable everywhere.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>MAE</td><td>mean(|y\u2212\u0177|)</td><td>Low \u2014 linear</td><td>Outliers common or noisy. Laplace noise assumption. Robust, but non-differentiable at 0.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Huber</td><td>MSE if |e|\u2264\u03b4, MAE otherwise</td><td>Tunable via \u03b4</td><td>MSE behaviour for small errors, outlier-robustness for large. Differentiable everywhere.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>MAPE</td><td>mean(|y\u2212\u0177|/|y|)\u00d7100</td><td>Explodes when y\u22480</td><td>Scale-independent %. Never when y can be 0.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>sMAPE</td><td>mean(2|y\u2212\u0177|/(|y|+|\u0177|))\u00d7100</td><td>Bounded [0,200]</td><td>MAPE variant that handles near-zero targets safely.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Cross-entropy</td><td>\u2212\u03a3y\u1d62log(\u0177\u1d62)</td><td>Very high for confident wrong preds</td><td>All classification. Probabilistic outputs required.</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">MAPE and near-zero targets \u2014 a real production failure</span>\n    <p>Electricity demand forecasting overnight: demand on a small feeder approaches 0.5 MW. Your model predicts 1.0 MW. MAPE = |0.5 \u2212 1.0|/0.5 \u00d7 100 = 100%. One near-zero interval dominates the entire metric. Solutions: use sMAPE, or compute MAPE only above a documented threshold (e.g., exclude intervals where demand &lt; 10% of peak), or use weighted MAPE where weight = actual demand (so low-demand periods contribute less).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. GRADIENT DESCENT \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-gd\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Gradient Descent</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition and the Adam math</span>\n    <p>Gradient descent: <strong>w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1 \u00b7 \u2207L(w)</strong>. The gradient \u2207L points toward steepest increase; stepping against it descends toward lower loss.<br><br>\n    <strong>Momentum SGD:</strong> velocity v \u2190 \u03b2v + (1\u2212\u03b2)g, w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1v. Accumulates gradient history \u2014 builds speed in consistent directions, dampens oscillations across ravines. \u03b2=0.9 typical.<br><br>\n    <strong>Adam:</strong> first moment (momentum): m \u2190 \u03b2\u2081m + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2081)g. Second moment (RMSProp): v \u2190 \u03b2\u2082v + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2082)g\u00b2. Bias correction (early steps biased low because m,v initialised at 0): m\u0302 = m/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2081\u1d57), v\u0302 = v/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2082\u1d57). Update: <strong>w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1 \u00b7 m\u0302 / (\u221av\u0302 + \u03b5)</strong>.<br><br>\n    The second moment normalises each parameter's update by its recent gradient magnitude \u2014 parameters with large recent gradients get smaller steps; parameters with tiny gradients get larger steps. \u03b2\u2081=0.9, \u03b2\u2082=0.999, \u03b5=1e-8, \u03b1=0.001 are near-universal defaults.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Variant</th><th>Batch size</th><th>Adaptive lr?</th><th>Best for</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Batch GD</td><td>Full dataset</td><td>No</td><td>Small datasets, convex problems. Rarely used in practice.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>SGD</td><td>1 sample</td><td>No</td><td>Online learning, streaming data.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Mini-batch SGD</td><td>32\u2013512</td><td>No</td><td>Standard for neural nets. GPU-efficient.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>SGD + Momentum</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>No</td><td>Deep nets where generalisation matters more than convergence speed.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Adam</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>Yes (per-param)</td><td>Default choice. Fast convergence. Can overfit on overparameterised models.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>AdamW</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>Yes</td><td>Adam + proper weight decay (decoupled from gradient). Standard for Transformers.</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Adam vs SGD \u2014 when SGD wins</span>\n    <p>Adam converges fast but can find sharp loss minima. Research shows that flatter minima generalise better \u2014 the model is less sensitive to small perturbations in weights. SGD with momentum tends to find flatter minima because its noisiness acts as implicit regularisation. For tabular ML (XGBoost, LightGBM): Adam is completely irrelevant \u2014 they use second-order gradients internally. For neural nets: Adam to train quickly, consider SGD fine-tuning at the end (SWATS) if you need the last bit of generalisation.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. REGULARISATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-reg\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Regularisation \u2014 L1 vs L2</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the constrained optimisation view</span>\n    <p>Regularisation adds a penalty to the loss that discourages large weights. The constrained optimisation view is more illuminating than the penalty view:<br><br>\n    <strong>L2 (Ridge):</strong> minimise Loss subject to \u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2 \u2264 t. Constraint region = sphere (L2 ball). Penalty gradient = 2\u03bbw (proportional to weight) \u2192 shrinks large weights faster, never reaches zero.<br><br>\n    <strong>L1 (Lasso):</strong> minimise Loss subject to \u03a3|w\u1d62| \u2264 t. Constraint region = diamond (L1 ball). Penalty gradient = \u03bb\u00b7sign(w) (constant magnitude regardless of weight size) \u2192 constant push drives weights all the way to zero.<br><br>\n    <strong>Elastic Net:</strong> \u03bb\u2081\u03a3|w\u1d62| + \u03bb\u2082\u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2. Both effects. Best when features are correlated and many are irrelevant.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why L1 produces zeros \u2014 the geometric argument</span>\n    <p>The solution is where the loss contour first touches the constraint boundary. The L2 ball (sphere) has a smooth curved surface \u2014 contours almost never touch it at an axis. Weights approach but never reach zero. The L1 ball (diamond) has corners exactly on the coordinate axes. Loss contours frequently first intersect the diamond at these corners \u2014 where one or more weights are exactly zero. The sparsity from L1 is geometric: the shape of the constraint region has corners on the axes.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">L1 with correlated features is unstable</span>\n    <p>If features A and B are highly correlated, Lasso zeroes out one and keeps the other \u2014 but which one is arbitrary (depends on random seed, data order). Run Lasso twice on slightly different data and you may get different features. For stable feature selection with correlated features: Elastic Net. For model stability: Ridge.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> RidgeCV, LassoCV, ElasticNetCV\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Always cross-validate the regularisation strength</span>\nridge = RidgeCV(alphas=[<span class=\"y\">0.001</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.01</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>, <span class=\"y\">100</span>], cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\nridge.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Best \u03b1: {ridge.alpha_}\"</span>)\n\nlasso = LassoCV(cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, max_iter=<span class=\"y\">5000</span>)\nlasso.fit(X_train, y_train)\nn_kept = (lasso.coef_ != <span class=\"y\">0</span>).sum()\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Lasso kept {n_kept}/{X.shape[1]} features\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. CROSS-VALIDATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-cv\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Cross-Validation</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 K-fold and its variants</span>\n    <p><strong>K-fold:</strong> split data into K folds. Train K times, each time holding out a different fold. Average K scores. Every point is in exactly one validation fold \u2014 more stable than one split. A single train/val split is sensitive to which examples happen to land in each set.<br><br>\n    <strong>Stratified K-fold:</strong> preserves class ratios in each fold. Essential for imbalanced classification \u2014 without stratification, some folds may have no minority class examples.<br><br>\n    <strong>TimeSeriesSplit:</strong> training window always ends before validation window. Standard K-fold shuffles \u2192 training on December to predict January \u2192 future leakage \u2192 falsely optimistic scores.<br><br>\n    <strong>Nested CV:</strong> outer loop (5 folds) evaluates model generalisation. Inner loop (3 folds) tunes hyperparameters within each outer training set. The outer score is unbiased because the test fold never influenced hyperparameter selection. Use when you need a rigorous unbiased estimate while also tuning.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Tuning hyperparameters and reporting the same CV score is biased</span>\n    <p>You run 5-fold CV, try 50 hyperparameter combinations, pick the best one, and report that CV score. The score is biased \u2014 you used the validation folds to pick hyperparameters. The folds are no longer held out. Nested CV fixes this: the inner loop tries hyperparameters, the outer loop measures performance of the whole procedure including tuning. If you have a true test set you've never touched, that solves it too: tune on CV, evaluate once on test.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> (StratifiedKFold, TimeSeriesSplit,\n    cross_val_score, GridSearchCV)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Stratified: for imbalanced classification</span>\nskf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, shuffle=<span class=\"y\">True</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nscores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=skf, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"AUC: {scores.mean():.4f} \u00b1 {scores.std():.4f}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Time series: training window always before validation</span>\ntscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> train_idx, val_idx <span class=\"k\">in</span> tscv.split(X):\n    <span class=\"c\"># val_idx is always AFTER train_idx chronologically</span>\n    pass\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Nested CV: unbiased estimate when hyperparameter tuning</span>\ninner_cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\nouter_cv  = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\ntuned_clf = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid={<span class=\"g\">'C'</span>: [<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>]}, cv=inner_cv)\nnested_scores = cross_val_score(tuned_clf, X, y, cv=outer_cv, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Unbiased AUC: {nested_scores.mean():.4f}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. FEATURE SCALING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-scale\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Feature Scaling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Which scaler when \u2014 and when not to scale</span>\n    <p><strong>StandardScaler:</strong> z = (x \u2212 \u03bc) / \u03c3. Assumes roughly Gaussian. Fails on heavy tails \u2014 one outlier compresses everything else.<br>\n    <strong>RobustScaler:</strong> uses median and IQR. Outliers don't influence it. Use when features have outliers.<br>\n    <strong>MinMaxScaler:</strong> scales to [0,1]. One outlier compresses all other values into a tiny range. Avoid unless you know the feature is bounded and clean.<br>\n    <strong>PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson):</strong> finds optimal power to make distribution Gaussian-like. Best for right-skewed features going into linear models.<br>\n    <strong>QuantileTransformer:</strong> maps to uniform or Gaussian. Destroys outlier information entirely.<br>\n    <strong>Tree-based models: no scaling needed.</strong> Splits are on thresholds \u2014 any monotone transformation doesn't change which split is best.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Always use Pipeline \u2014 the only correct way to scale with CV</span>\n    <p>Fitting the scaler on the full dataset before splitting leaks test statistics (mean, std) into training. Always use Pipeline so the scaler is fit only on the training fold within each CV fold. One line fixes this permanently.</p>\n    <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> RobustScaler\n\n<span class=\"c\"># The scaler is fit per fold inside cross_val_score \u2014 no leakage</span>\npipe = Pipeline([(<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, RobustScaler()), (<span class=\"g\">'model'</span>, your_model)])\ncross_val_score(pipe, X, y, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-qa\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain the bias-variance tradeoff with the mathematical decomposition.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">E[(y\u2212f\u0302)\u00b2] = Bias\u00b2[f\u0302] + Var[f\u0302] + \u03c3\u00b2. Bias = E[f\u0302(x)] \u2212 f(x): systematic error \u2014 how far the average prediction (over all possible training sets of size n) is from the true function. A linear model fit to quadratic data has high bias regardless of data size. Variance = E[(f\u0302(x) \u2212 E[f\u0302(x)])\u00b2]: how much predictions change when trained on different datasets of the same size. A degree-9 polynomial changes wildly between datasets. \u03c3\u00b2 is irreducible noise. Practical diagnosis: high train error = bias (model too simple). Large train-val gap = variance (memorising noise). The tradeoff: reducing bias by adding model complexity typically increases variance. You cannot minimise both simultaneously \u2014 find the sweet spot.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does L1 produce sparse weights but L2 doesn't? Give the geometric argument.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Frame both as constrained optimisation. L2: minimise loss subject to \u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2 \u2264 t \u2014 constraint region is a sphere. L1: minimise loss subject to \u03a3|w\u1d62| \u2264 t \u2014 constraint region is a diamond. The solution is where the loss contour first touches the constraint boundary. The L2 sphere has a smooth curved surface \u2014 loss contours almost never intersect it at an axis. Weights approach but never reach zero. The L1 diamond has corners exactly on the coordinate axes. Loss contours frequently first intersect the diamond at these corners \u2014 where one or more w\u1d62 = 0. The sparsity is not a property of the penalty magnitude \u2014 it is a property of the geometry of the L1 constraint region.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is Adam? How does it differ from SGD with momentum?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Both maintain a first moment (running average of gradients = momentum): m \u2190 \u03b2\u2081m + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2081)g. Adam additionally maintains a second moment \u2014 running average of squared gradients: v \u2190 \u03b2\u2082v + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2082)g\u00b2. After bias correction (m\u0302, v\u0302), the update is w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u00b7m\u0302/(\u221av\u0302 + \u03b5). The second moment adapts the learning rate per parameter \u2014 parameters with large recent gradients get smaller updates; those with small gradients get larger updates. SGD+Momentum uses the same learning rate for every parameter. Adam is faster to converge because it scales updates appropriately per parameter automatically. SGD sometimes finds better generalising solutions for overparameterised neural nets because its noisiness acts as implicit regularisation, finding flatter minima.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When do you use each type of cross-validation?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Standard K-fold: regression or balanced classification. Stratified K-fold: imbalanced classification \u2014 preserves class ratios in each fold, ensuring every fold has minority class examples. TimeSeriesSplit: any time-series data \u2014 training window always ends before validation window, no future leakage. Standard K-fold on time series gives falsely optimistic scores because it allows training on December to predict January. Nested CV: when you're tuning hyperparameters and need an unbiased estimate of generalisation at the same time. Outer loop (5 folds) evaluates the whole procedure; inner loop (3 folds) tunes hyperparameters. If you have a true held-out test set you've never touched, you don't need nested CV \u2014 tune on CV, evaluate once on test.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_fundamentals": "<main>\n  <h1>ML Fundamentals</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Bias-Variance Tradeoff</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The central tension \u2014 with the math</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Regularisation \u2014 L1 vs L2</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Geometric intuition, not just \"penalty\"</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Cross-Validation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">K-fold, stratified, time-series, nested CV</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Feature Scaling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">When it matters, which scaler, data leakage</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Loss Functions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">MSE, MAE, Huber, cross-entropy \u2014 which and why</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Gradient Descent</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Variants, momentum, Adam, lr scheduling</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Linear Regression \u2014 deep</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">OLS, normal equation, assumptions, diagnostics</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Logistic Regression \u2014 deep</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Probabilistic view, MLE, decision boundary</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Total error = Bias\u00b2 + Variance + Irreducible noise.</strong> Bias = how wrong the model is on average across different datasets. Variance = how much predictions change across datasets. You can't reduce both simultaneously \u2014 this is the tradeoff.</li>\n      <li><strong>L2 (Ridge):</strong> penalty = \u03bb\u03a3w\u00b2. Gradient of penalty = 2\u03bbw \u2014 proportional to w, so large weights shrink faster. No weight ever hits exactly zero. Geometric: the L2 constraint region is a sphere \u2014 the optimal point almost never lands on an axis.</li>\n      <li><strong>L1 (Lasso):</strong> penalty = \u03bb\u03a3|w|. Gradient of penalty = \u03bb\u00b7sign(w) \u2014 constant magnitude regardless of w size. Drives weights all the way to zero. Geometric: L2 constraint is a diamond \u2014 optimal point frequently lands on a corner (axis = zero weight).</li>\n      <li><strong>K-fold CV:</strong> every data point appears in exactly one validation fold. More reliable than one split. Stratified = preserve class ratios. TimeSeriesSplit = no future leakage. Nested CV = outer loop for model selection, inner loop for hyperparameter tuning.</li>\n      <li><strong>Scale when:</strong> distance-based (KNN, SVM, KMeans), gradient descent (linear, logistic, neural nets), PCA. Never scale for tree-based models.</li>\n      <li><strong>Normal equation:</strong> w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y. Closed-form OLS solution. O(n\u00b7d\u00b2) \u2014 fast for small d, impractical when d &gt; ~10K. Requires X\u1d40X invertible (fails with multicollinearity).</li>\n      <li><strong>Logistic regression:</strong> models P(y=1|x) = \u03c3(w\u1d40x). \u03c3 = sigmoid. Trained by minimising negative log-likelihood = cross-entropy. Decision boundary = linear in feature space.</li>\n      <li><strong>Adam = momentum + RMSProp.</strong> First moment (momentum) smooths gradient direction. Second moment (RMSProp) adapts lr per parameter. Bias correction in early steps. Usually works out of box \u2014 but SGD sometimes generalises better for overparameterised models.</li>\n      <li><strong>MSE vs MAE:</strong> MSE squares errors \u2014 outliers dominate. MAE is linear \u2014 outliers matter less. For load forecasting: MSE if large spikes are catastrophic, MAE if outliers are noise you want to ignore, MAPE for percentage error (compare across different load magnitudes).</li>\n      <li><strong>OLS assumptions (LINE):</strong> Linearity, Independence of errors, Normally distributed errors, Equal variance (homoscedasticity). Violations \u2192 biased/inconsistent estimates or wrong confidence intervals.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. BIAS-VARIANCE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-bv\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Bias-Variance Tradeoff</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 with the math</span>\n    <p>For a model f\u0302 trained on dataset D, predicting target y = f(x) + \u03b5 (where \u03b5 is irreducible noise with variance \u03c3\u00b2), the expected prediction error at point x decomposes as:</p>\n    <p><strong>E[(y \u2212 f\u0302(x))\u00b2] = Bias[f\u0302(x)]\u00b2 + Var[f\u0302(x)] + \u03c3\u00b2</strong></p>\n    <p>where <strong>Bias[f\u0302(x)] = E[f\u0302(x)] \u2212 f(x)</strong> (how far the average prediction is from truth across all possible training sets) and <strong>Var[f\u0302(x)] = E[(f\u0302(x) \u2212 E[f\u0302(x)])\u00b2]</strong> (how much predictions vary across different training sets of the same size). \u03c3\u00b2 is irreducible \u2014 no model eliminates it.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">What this means practically</span>\n    <p>Train the same model architecture 100 times on 100 different training sets drawn from the same distribution. Bias asks: is the average of 100 predictions close to the true value? Variance asks: how spread out are those 100 predictions around their average?<br><br>\n    A linear model fit to sinusoidal data: every training set produces roughly the same wrong line (low variance, high bias). A degree-20 polynomial: each training set produces a wildly different wiggly curve (low bias per set, high variance across sets).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 195\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"17\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--ink)\">Bias-Variance: diagnosing from train/val error</text>\n      <rect x=\"15\" y=\"27\" width=\"205\" height=\"158\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--red)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--red)\">High Bias (Underfitting)</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Gap is small \u2014 both are bad</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">Fix: more complexity,</text>\n      <text x=\"117\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--red)\">more features, less \u03bb</text>\n      <rect x=\"245\" y=\"27\" width=\"205\" height=\"158\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--green)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--green)\">Sweet Spot</text>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: LOW</text>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: LOW and \u2248 train</text>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Small gap, both errors low</text>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">This is what you want.</text>\n      <text x=\"347\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--green)\">The actual goal.</text>\n      <rect x=\"475\" y=\"27\" width=\"210\" height=\"158\" rx=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber-dim)\" stroke=\"var(--amber)\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"48\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">High Variance (Overfitting)</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"66\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Train error: LOW</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"var(--ink2)\">Val error: HIGH</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--ink3)\">Large gap \u2014 memorised train</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">Fix: more data, larger \u03bb,</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"var(--amber)\">simpler model, early stop</text>\n    </svg>\n    <figcaption>Diagnose before prescribing. High train error = bias problem. Large train-val gap = variance problem. Different causes, different fixes.</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. REGULARISATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-reg\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Regularisation \u2014 L1 vs L2</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>Regularisation adds a penalty to the loss function that discourages large weights. The constrained optimisation view is more illuminating than the penalty view: you are minimising the loss subject to the constraint that weights live within a bounded region. The shape of that region determines whether weights hit zero.</p>\n    <p><strong>L2 (Ridge):</strong> Loss + \u03bb\u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2 \u2192 constrained to an L2 ball (sphere in weight space).<br>\n    <strong>L1 (Lasso):</strong> Loss + \u03bb\u03a3|w\u1d62| \u2192 constrained to an L1 ball (diamond/octahedron in weight space).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why L1 produces zeros and L2 doesn't \u2014 the geometric argument</span>\n    <p>Draw the loss function contours (ellipses) and the constraint region. The optimal point is where a loss contour first touches the constraint region.<br><br>\n    An L2 ball (sphere) has a smooth curved surface \u2014 the loss contour almost never touches it at an axis, so weights almost never become exactly zero.<br><br>\n    An L1 ball (diamond) has corners that lie exactly on the axes. The loss contour very frequently first touches the diamond at one of these corners \u2014 where one or more weights are exactly zero. The more features, the more corners, the more likely zero solutions are. This is why L1 does feature selection: it literally pushes weights to corners of the constraint region.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">L1 and correlated features \u2014 it picks one arbitrarily</span>\n    <p>If features A and B are perfectly correlated, L1 will zero out one and keep the other \u2014 but which one is arbitrary (depends on initialisation, data order). This is unstable: run Lasso twice on slightly different data, you might get A one time and B the next. L2 distributes weight across correlated features stably. Elastic Net is the right answer when you have both correlated features and many irrelevant ones.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> Ridge, Lasso, ElasticNet, RidgeCV, LassoCV\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Ridge: shrinks all weights, none reach zero</span>\nridge = Ridge(alpha=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># alpha = \u03bb regularisation strength</span>\nridge.fit(X_train, y_train)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Lasso: drives some weights to exactly zero \u2192 feature selection</span>\nlasso = Lasso(alpha=<span class=\"y\">0.01</span>)\nlasso.fit(X_train, y_train)\nn_nonzero = (lasso.coef_ != <span class=\"y\">0</span>).sum()\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Lasso kept {n_nonzero}/{X.shape[1]} features\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Find optimal alpha with cross-validation (built-in, much faster than GridSearch)</span>\nridge_cv = RidgeCV(alphas=[<span class=\"y\">0.001</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.01</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1.0</span>, <span class=\"y\">10.0</span>, <span class=\"y\">100.0</span>], cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\nridge_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Best \u03b1: {ridge_cv.alpha_}\"</span>)\n\nlasso_cv = LassoCV(cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, max_iter=<span class=\"y\">5000</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># searches \u03b1 automatically</span>\nlasso_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)</div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Property</th><th>L2 Ridge</th><th>L1 Lasso</th><th>Elastic Net</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Penalty</td><td>\u03bb\u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2</td><td>\u03bb\u03a3|w\u1d62|</td><td>\u03bb\u2081\u03a3|w\u1d62| + \u03bb\u2082\u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Gradient of penalty</td><td>2\u03bbw \u2014 shrinks proportionally</td><td>\u03bb\u00b7sign(w) \u2014 constant push to zero</td><td>Both</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Weights \u2192 exactly 0?</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Correlated features</td><td>Distributes weight evenly</td><td>Picks one, zeros others (arbitrary)</td><td>Groups them</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Use when</td><td>All features matter somewhat</td><td>Most features irrelevant, want sparse model</td><td>Many features, some correlated, some irrelevant</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. CROSS-VALIDATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-cv\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Cross-Validation</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 K-Fold and its variants</span>\n    <p>A method to estimate generalisation error by training and evaluating K times, each time on a different held-out fold. Every data point appears in exactly one validation fold, giving a more stable estimate than a single train/val split. Variants: <strong>Stratified K-Fold</strong> \u2014 preserves class ratios (critical for imbalanced data). <strong>TimeSeriesSplit</strong> \u2014 training window always precedes validation window, no future leakage. <strong>Nested CV</strong> \u2014 outer loop evaluates model, inner loop tunes hyperparameters.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Nested CV \u2014 the right way to tune and evaluate simultaneously</span>\n    <p>The wrong approach: tune hyperparameters using K-fold CV, then report that CV score as your model's generalisation estimate. The problem: you used the validation data to pick hyperparameters \u2014 the \"validation\" set is no longer held out. The score is optimistically biased.<br><br>\n    Nested CV: outer loop (5 folds) gives 5 hold-out test sets. For each outer fold, inner loop (3 folds) tunes hyperparameters on the remaining data. Report the average outer test score. More expensive (15 model fits minimum) but the reported score is unbiased.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Time series: standard K-fold leaks the future</span>\n    <p>K-fold shuffles data before splitting. For a time series, fold 3 might contain January data while fold 2 contains December. When fold 3 is validation and fold 2 is in training, the model effectively trains on data from after its validation period \u2014 it has seen the future. TimeSeriesSplit enforces strict temporal ordering: training window always ends before validation window starts.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> (cross_val_score, StratifiedKFold,\n    TimeSeriesSplit, cross_validate, GridSearchCV)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Stratified K-fold: preserves class ratios per fold</span>\nskf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, shuffle=<span class=\"y\">True</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nscores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=skf, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"AUC: {scores.mean():.4f} \u00b1 {scores.std():.4f}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Time series split: expanding training window</span>\ntscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> train_idx, val_idx <span class=\"k\">in</span> tscv.split(X):\n    X_tr, X_val = X.iloc[train_idx], X.iloc[val_idx]\n    <span class=\"c\"># val_idx is always AFTER train_idx \u2014 no future leakage</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Nested CV: unbiased estimate when tuning hyperparameters</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> cross_val_score, GridSearchCV\n\ninner_cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\nouter_cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Inner CV tunes hyperparameters</span>\nclf = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid={<span class=\"g\">'C'</span>: [<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>]}, cv=inner_cv)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Outer CV evaluates the whole procedure (including tuning)</span>\nnested_scores = cross_val_score(clf, X, y, cv=outer_cv, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Unbiased AUC: {nested_scores.mean():.4f}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. FEATURE SCALING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-scale\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Feature Scaling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 and which scaler to use when</span>\n    <p><strong>StandardScaler:</strong> z = (x \u2212 \u03bc) / \u03c3. Works when distribution is roughly Gaussian. Fails badly with heavy tails or outliers (one outlier shifts \u03bc and inflates \u03c3 dramatically).<br>\n    <strong>MinMaxScaler:</strong> scales to [0,1]. Sensitive to outliers \u2014 one outlier compresses everything else to a tiny range.<br>\n    <strong>RobustScaler:</strong> uses median and IQR. Outliers don't affect it. Use for skewed data with outliers.<br>\n    <strong>QuantileTransformer:</strong> maps to uniform or Gaussian distribution. Handles heavy tails. Destroys outlier information entirely.<br>\n    <strong>PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson):</strong> finds the optimal power transform to make data more Gaussian-like. Best for skewed features going into linear models.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Fit scaler on training data only \u2014 always</span>\n    <p>Fitting the scaler on the full dataset uses test set statistics (mean, std, min, max) to scale training data. The model has effectively seen summary statistics of the test set during training \u2014 this is data leakage. Scores will be optimistically biased. The fix is two lines: <code>scaler.fit(X_train)</code> then <code>scaler.transform(X_test)</code>. In a pipeline, sklearn handles this automatically \u2014 another reason to always use Pipeline.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> (StandardScaler, RobustScaler,\n    PowerTransformer, QuantileTransformer)\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n\n<span class=\"c\"># WRONG: leaks test statistics</span>\nscaler = StandardScaler().fit(X)          <span class=\"c\"># sees all data \u2190 leak</span>\nX_scaled = scaler.transform(X)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># RIGHT: Pipeline handles fit/transform split automatically</span>\npipe = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, RobustScaler()),          <span class=\"c\"># fit only on training fold</span>\n    (<span class=\"g\">'model'</span>,  YourModel())\n])\ncross_val_score(pipe, X, y, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)        <span class=\"c\"># scaler fit per fold \u2014 no leakage</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Choosing the right scaler:</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Gaussian-ish features           \u2192 StandardScaler</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Features with outliers           \u2192 RobustScaler</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Skewed features \u2192 linear model  \u2192 PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Very skewed / long-tailed       \u2192 QuantileTransformer</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Tree-based models                \u2192 no scaler needed at all</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. LOSS FUNCTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-loss\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Loss Functions \u2014 which and why</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>A loss function maps (prediction, truth) \u2192 scalar measuring wrongness. Training minimises the average loss. The loss choice encodes your assumptions about the error distribution and what kinds of mistakes matter most. MSE assumes Gaussian errors. MAE assumes Laplace errors. Cross-entropy assumes Bernoulli/multinomial. Mismatching loss to problem structure produces suboptimal models even with perfect architecture.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">MSE vs MAE vs MAPE \u2014 the load forecasting case</span>\n    <p>You forecast electricity demand at 96 15-minute intervals. MSE: a 500 MW error at midnight is penalised 25,000\u00d7 more than a 50 MW error at noon \u2014 whether that's appropriate depends on whether large errors are catastrophically costly or just proportionally costly. MAE: a 500 MW error is simply 10\u00d7 a 50 MW error. MAPE: errors are in percentage terms \u2014 useful when comparing accuracy across seasons where absolute demand varies 2\u00d7 between summer and winter. For BRPL/BYPL load forecasting, MAPE is the right metric because regulators benchmark it across diverse demand periods.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Loss</th><th>Formula</th><th>Outlier sensitivity</th><th>Use when</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>MSE</td><td>mean((y\u2212\u0177)\u00b2)</td><td>High \u2014 squares errors</td><td>Large errors are disproportionately costly. Gaussian noise assumption.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>MAE</td><td>mean(|y\u2212\u0177|)</td><td>Low \u2014 linear penalty</td><td>Outliers are common/noisy. Laplace noise assumption.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Huber</td><td>MSE if |e|\u2264\u03b4, MAE otherwise</td><td>Tunable via \u03b4</td><td>Want MSE behaviour for small errors, robustness for large ones.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>MAPE</td><td>mean(|y\u2212\u0177|/|y|)\u00d7100</td><td>High \u2014 explodes when y\u22480</td><td>Comparing accuracy across different scales. Never use if y can be 0.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Cross-entropy</td><td>\u2212\u03a3y\u1d62log(\u0177\u1d62)</td><td>Very high for confident wrong predictions</td><td>All classification. Probabilistic output needed.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Hinge</td><td>max(0, 1\u2212y\u00b7\u0177)</td><td>Moderate</td><td>SVMs. Margin-based classification.</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. GRADIENT DESCENT \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-gd\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Gradient Descent \u2014 variants and learning rate</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>Gradient descent iteratively updates weights by stepping in the negative gradient direction: <strong>w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1 \u00b7 \u2207L(w)</strong>, where \u03b1 is the learning rate and \u2207L(w) is the gradient of the loss w.r.t. all weights. The gradient points toward steepest increase; stepping against it descends toward lower loss.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Momentum and Adam \u2014 the actual math</span>\n    <p><strong>Momentum SGD:</strong> instead of updating with the raw gradient, maintain a velocity v that accumulates gradients: v \u2190 \u03b2v + (1\u2212\u03b2)\u2207L, w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1v. Momentum \u03b2 (typically 0.9) acts like a ball rolling downhill \u2014 it builds up speed in consistent directions and dampens oscillations across ravines.<br><br>\n    <strong>Adam:</strong> maintains two moments. First moment (momentum): m \u2190 \u03b2\u2081m + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2081)g. Second moment (RMSProp): v \u2190 \u03b2\u2082v + (1\u2212\u03b2\u2082)g\u00b2. Bias correction: m\u0302 = m/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2081\u1d57), v\u0302 = v/(1\u2212\u03b2\u2082\u1d57). Update: w \u2190 w \u2212 \u03b1\u00b7m\u0302/(\u221av\u0302 + \u03b5). The second moment adapts the learning rate per parameter: parameters with large recent gradients get smaller updates. Parameters with small gradients get larger updates. \u03b2\u2081=0.9, \u03b2\u2082=0.999, \u03b5=1e-8 are near-universal defaults.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">When SGD beats Adam \u2014 and why this matters</span>\n    <p>Adam converges faster but can generalise worse. In overparameterised models (neural nets with more parameters than data), Adam finds a sharp minimum that generalises poorly. SGD with momentum finds a flatter minimum that generalises better \u2014 the \"width\" of the minimum correlates with generalisation. For tabular ML with XGBoost/LightGBM, Adam is irrelevant (they use second-order gradients, not GD). For neural nets on production tasks: Adam to train quickly, potentially switch to SGD at the end for the final generalisation push. This is called \"Adam then SGD\" or SWATS.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Variant</th><th>Batch size</th><th>Adaptive lr?</th><th>When</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Batch GD</td><td>Full dataset</td><td>No</td><td>Small datasets, convex problems</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>SGD</td><td>1 sample</td><td>No</td><td>Online learning, very large datasets</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Mini-batch SGD</td><td>32\u2013512</td><td>No</td><td>Standard for neural nets, GPU-efficient</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>SGD + Momentum</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>No</td><td>Better generalisation than Adam for deep nets</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Adam</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>Yes (per-param)</td><td>Default choice; fast convergence</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>AdamW</td><td>Mini-batch</td><td>Yes</td><td>Adam + proper weight decay (not L2). Transformers standard.</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 07. LINEAR REGRESSION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-linreg\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Linear Regression \u2014 OLS, normal equation, assumptions</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 OLS and the Normal Equation</span>\n    <p>Linear regression models \u0177 = Xw where X is the n\u00d7(d+1) design matrix (with a column of 1s for bias). OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) minimises \u03a3(y\u1d62 \u2212 \u0177\u1d62)\u00b2 = ||y \u2212 Xw||\u00b2. Taking the gradient and setting to zero: \u2202L/\u2202w = \u22122X\u1d40(y \u2212 Xw) = 0 \u2192 X\u1d40Xw = X\u1d40y. Solving: <strong>w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y</strong>. This is the normal equation \u2014 a closed-form solution.<br><br>\n    Complexity: O(nd\u00b2) for X\u1d40y, O(d\u00b3) for matrix inversion. Practical limit: d \u2272 10,000. For larger d, gradient descent is faster. X\u1d40X must be invertible \u2014 fails with multicollinearity (perfectly correlated features). Ridge regression stabilises this by adding \u03bbI: w = (X\u1d40X + \u03bbI)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">What OLS is actually doing geometrically</span>\n    <p>The columns of X span a d-dimensional subspace of \u211d\u207f. The vector y (your labels) almost certainly does not lie in this subspace \u2014 no exact linear combination of features equals y exactly. OLS finds the point \u0177 in the column space of X that is closest to y. That closest point is the orthogonal projection of y onto the column space of X. The residuals (y \u2212 \u0177) are perpendicular to that subspace \u2014 which is exactly what X\u1d40(y \u2212 \u0177) = 0 means.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">OLS assumptions \u2014 which violations actually matter</span>\n    <p><strong>Linearity:</strong> E[y|X] = Xw. Violation \u2192 biased estimates. Check with residual vs fitted plot. <strong>Independence:</strong> errors uncorrelated across observations. Violation in time series (autocorrelation) \u2192 wrong standard errors, invalid inference. Check with Durbin-Watson test. <strong>Homoscedasticity:</strong> Var(\u03b5|X) = \u03c3\u00b2. Violation \u2192 inefficient estimates, wrong SEs. Check: residuals vs fitted should be a horizontal band. <strong>Normality of residuals:</strong> needed for valid t-tests and CIs, not for OLS coefficient estimates themselves. Check with Q-Q plot. Normality matters least \u2014 OLS coefficients are still unbiased with non-normal errors (CLT saves you for large n).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LinearRegression\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> statsmodels.api <span class=\"k\">as</span> sm\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Normal equation (direct, for small d)</span>\nX_b = np.c_[np.ones(len(X_train)), X_train]   <span class=\"c\"># add bias column</span>\nw_ols = np.linalg.lstsq(X_b, y_train, rcond=<span class=\"k\">None</span>)[<span class=\"y\">0</span>]   <span class=\"c\"># numerically stable</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Note: lstsq is preferred over np.linalg.inv(X.T@X) @ X.T@y</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2014 it handles near-singular X\u1d40X gracefully via SVD</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># sklearn OLS</span>\nmodel = LinearRegression()\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Coefficients: {model.coef_}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Intercept: {model.intercept_}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># statsmodels for diagnostics (p-values, confidence intervals, tests)</span>\nX_sm = sm.add_constant(X_train)\nols = sm.OLS(y_train, X_sm).fit()\nprint(ols.summary())   <span class=\"c\"># R\u00b2, adj-R\u00b2, F-stat, p-values, confidence intervals</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Diagnostic plots</span>\nresiduals = y_train - model.predict(X_train)\n<span class=\"c\"># 1. Residuals vs fitted \u2014 check linearity and homoscedasticity</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># 2. Q-Q plot \u2014 check normality of residuals</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># 3. Scale-location \u2014 check homoscedasticity more clearly</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># 4. Leverage plot \u2014 identify influential outliers</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 08. LOGISTIC REGRESSION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-logreg\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Logistic Regression \u2014 probabilistic view</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the probabilistic interpretation</span>\n    <p>Logistic regression models the probability of a class: <strong>P(y=1|x) = \u03c3(w\u1d40x + b)</strong> where \u03c3(z) = 1/(1+e\u207b\u1dbb) is the sigmoid function mapping any real number to (0,1).<br><br>\n    Equivalently: log(P(y=1)/P(y=0)) = w\u1d40x + b. The left side is the log-odds (logit). Logistic regression is a linear model in log-odds space.<br><br>\n    Training minimises the negative log-likelihood: L = \u2212\u03a3[y\u1d62log(\u0177\u1d62) + (1\u2212y\u1d62)log(1\u2212\u0177\u1d62)]. This is exactly binary cross-entropy. No closed-form solution exists \u2014 trained with gradient descent (or IRLS for small data).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why logistic regression is a linear classifier</span>\n    <p>The decision boundary is where P(y=1|x) = 0.5, which means \u03c3(w\u1d40x) = 0.5, which means w\u1d40x = 0. This is a hyperplane \u2014 a linear boundary in feature space. Logistic regression cannot learn a circle, a spiral, or any non-linear boundary in the original features. Add polynomial features first, or use a non-linear model.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Logistic regression is not regression \u2014 do not use R\u00b2</span>\n    <p>Despite the name, logistic regression is a classification model. It outputs probabilities and has a linear decision boundary. Evaluating it with R\u00b2 is meaningless. Evaluate with: log-loss (the actual training objective), AUC-ROC (threshold-free ranking quality), precision-recall AUC (for imbalanced data). The coefficient interpretation also changes: a coefficient w\u2c7c means a one-unit increase in feature j multiplies the odds by e^w\u2c7c \u2014 this is the odds ratio, not a linear effect size.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LogisticRegression\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> roc_auc_score, log_loss\n\nmodel = LogisticRegression(\n    C=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>,             <span class=\"c\"># C = 1/\u03bb \u2014 inverse regularisation strength</span>\n    penalty=<span class=\"g\">'l2'</span>,      <span class=\"c\"># L2 by default; 'l1' for feature selection</span>\n    solver=<span class=\"g\">'lbfgs'</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># 'liblinear' for L1; 'saga' for large datasets</span>\n    max_iter=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>,\n    class_weight=<span class=\"g\">'balanced'</span>   <span class=\"c\"># adjust for imbalance</span>\n)\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Probabilities \u2014 not just class labels</span>\ny_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, <span class=\"y\">1</span>]   <span class=\"c\"># P(y=1|x)</span>\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"AUC-ROC: {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob):.4f}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Log-loss: {log_loss(y_test, y_prob):.4f}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Coefficient interpretation</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\nodds_ratios = np.exp(model.coef_[<span class=\"y\">0</span>])\n<span class=\"c\"># odds_ratios[j] > 1 \u2192 feature j increases probability of y=1</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># odds_ratios[j] < 1 \u2192 feature j decreases probability of y=1</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 Q&A \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"ml-qa\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain the bias-variance tradeoff. What is the mathematical decomposition?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Expected prediction error at point x = Bias\u00b2[f\u0302(x)] + Var[f\u0302(x)] + \u03c3\u00b2. Bias is E[f\u0302(x)] \u2212 f(x) \u2014 how far the average prediction across all possible training sets is from the true function. Variance is E[(f\u0302(x) \u2212 E[f\u0302(x)])\u00b2] \u2014 how much predictions vary across training sets. \u03c3\u00b2 is irreducible noise. To see the tradeoff: a linear model fit to non-linear data has high bias (always wrong in the same direction) but low variance (similar prediction regardless of training set). A high-degree polynomial has low bias (flexible enough to capture the truth) but high variance (wildly different curves on different datasets). Practical diagnosis: high train error = bias. Large train-val gap = variance. Different problems, different fixes.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does L1 produce sparse weights but L2 doesn't? Use the geometric argument.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Frame both as constrained optimisation. L2: minimise loss subject to \u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2 \u2264 t. The constraint region is a sphere. L1: minimise loss subject to \u03a3|w\u1d62| \u2264 t. The constraint region is a diamond (L1 ball). The optimal solution is where the loss contour first touches the constraint region. The diamond has corners lying exactly on the coordinate axes \u2014 these corners correspond to zero weights. Loss contours (roughly elliptical) very frequently first intersect the diamond at these corners, setting one or more weights to exactly zero. The sphere has no corners \u2014 a smooth curved surface \u2014 so the loss contour almost never touches it at an axis, and weights almost never reach zero. The sparsity from L1 is a geometric consequence of the shape of the L1 ball, not the magnitude of the penalty.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the normal equation? When would you use it vs gradient descent?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y. Closed-form OLS solution derived by setting the gradient of the loss to zero. Requires O(d\u00b3) matrix inversion. Use when: number of features d is small (d \u2272 10,000) and you want an exact solution without hyperparameter tuning (no learning rate to set). Gradient descent when: d is large (matrix inversion becomes impractical), data doesn't fit in memory (mini-batch SGD), or you're using regularisation (Ridge adds \u03bbI to X\u1d40X before inverting \u2014 still closed form; Lasso has no closed form). In practice, sklearn's LinearRegression uses least-squares via SVD (more stable than direct inversion), and LogisticRegression always uses gradient methods (no closed form).</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is Adam and how does it differ from SGD with momentum?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Both maintain a running average of gradients (first moment / momentum). Adam additionally maintains a running average of squared gradients (second moment / RMSProp component). The second moment normalises each parameter update by the square root of the recent gradient magnitude for that parameter \u2014 parameters with large recent gradients get smaller updates; parameters with small gradients get larger updates. This per-parameter adaptive learning rate is what makes Adam fast \u2014 it automatically scales updates appropriately per parameter. SGD with momentum uses the same learning rate for every parameter. Bias correction (dividing by 1\u2212\u03b2\u1d57) corrects the fact that the moment estimates are initialised at zero and are biased low in early iterations. When does SGD beat Adam? Overparameterised deep nets \u2014 Adam finds sharper minima that generalise worse. SGD's noisiness acts as implicit regularisation, finding flatter, more generalisable minima.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What are the assumptions of OLS linear regression? Which violations actually matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">LINE: Linearity (E[y|X] = Xw), Independence of errors, Normality of errors, Equal variance (homoscedasticity). Severity of violations: Linearity violations cause biased estimates \u2014 serious. Fix: add polynomial features or use a non-linear model. Independence violations (autocorrelation in time series) cause wrong standard errors and invalid confidence intervals \u2014 standard errors are too small, making everything look significant. Fix: include lag features, use time-series-aware models, or correct SEs with Newey-West. Homoscedasticity violations cause inefficient estimates and wrong SEs. Fix: log-transform the target (common for right-skewed outcomes like demand), or use WLS. Normality of residuals matters least \u2014 the CLT means OLS coefficients are approximately normally distributed for large n regardless of residual distribution. Only matters for small samples with inference on individual coefficients.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What does the coefficient in logistic regression actually mean?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Logistic regression models log-odds: log(P(y=1)/P(y=0)) = \u03a3w\u2c7cx\u2c7c + b. Coefficient w\u2c7c means: a one-unit increase in feature j increases the log-odds by w\u2c7c, which multiplies the odds by e^w\u2c7c. If w\u2c7c = 0.5, then e^0.5 \u2248 1.65 \u2014 a one-unit increase in feature j multiplies the odds of y=1 by 1.65 (65% increase in odds). This is an odds ratio, not a probability ratio. Probabilities are non-linear in features (via sigmoid), so there's no single \"effect on probability\" \u2014 the effect on probability depends on where you are on the sigmoid curve. At P\u22480.5 (the steep part), a small change in a feature has a large effect on probability. At P\u22480.01, the same change has a tiny effect on probability.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_regression": "<main>\n  <h1>Regression Algorithms</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Linear Regression</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">OLS, normal equation, geometric interpretation</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">OLS Assumptions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">LINE \u2014 which violations actually matter</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Ridge Regression (L2)</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Shrinkage, multicollinearity, when to use</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Lasso Regression (L1)</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Feature selection, sparsity, instability</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Elastic Net</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">When correlated features need both L1+L2</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Polynomial Regression</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Non-linearity via feature expansion</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Normal equation \u2014 when to use and when not:</strong> w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y is the closed-form OLS solution. O(d\u00b3) for matrix inversion. Use when d &lt; ~10,000 features. Above that, gradient descent is faster. X\u1d40X must be invertible \u2014 fails with perfect multicollinearity (two features exactly linearly dependent). Ridge fixes this: w = (X\u1d40X + \u03bbI)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y \u2014 \u03bbI makes the matrix strictly positive definite, always invertible.</li>\n    <li><strong>OLS geometric view:</strong> the label vector y almost certainly doesn't lie in the column space of X. OLS finds \u0177 \u2014 the orthogonal projection of y onto that subspace. Residuals (y \u2212 \u0177) are perpendicular to every feature column by construction. This geometric view explains why OLS residuals are always uncorrelated with fitted values \u2014 it's a mathematical consequence, not a coincidence.</li>\n    <li><strong>Which OLS assumption matters most in practice:</strong> Independence (no autocorrelation) is the most dangerous violation for time-series work \u2014 it makes standard errors wrong and everything appear statistically significant when it isn't. Check with Durbin-Watson test. Normality of residuals matters least \u2014 OLS coefficients are unbiased without it; only inference on individual coefficients requires it.</li>\n    <li><strong>L1 instability with correlated features:</strong> if features A and B are highly correlated, Lasso zeros out one and keeps the other \u2014 but which one is arbitrary (depends on seed, data order). Running Lasso twice on slightly different data may select different features. For stable feature selection from correlated groups: Elastic Net, or stability selection (run Lasso many times on bootstraps, keep features that appear consistently).</li>\n    <li><strong>Polynomial regression overfits fast:</strong> degree 2 on 10 features = 66 features. Degree 3 = 286. Feature explosion makes overfitting nearly certain without regularisation. Always pair polynomial features with Ridge. In practice: tree-based models handle non-linear interactions without explicit polynomial terms and don't need this feature explosion.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. LINEAR REGRESSION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-linear\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Linear Regression \u2014 OLS</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 OLS and the Normal Equation</span>\n    <p>Linear regression: \u0177 = Xw, where X is the n\u00d7(d+1) design matrix (with a column of 1s for the bias/intercept). OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) minimises the sum of squared residuals: ||y \u2212 Xw||\u00b2.<br><br>\n    Taking the gradient and setting to zero:<br>\n    \u2202/\u2202w ||y \u2212 Xw||\u00b2 = \u22122X\u1d40(y \u2212 Xw) = 0<br>\n    \u2192 X\u1d40Xw = X\u1d40y<br><br>\n    Solving: <strong>w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y</strong> \u2014 the Normal Equation.<br><br>\n    Complexity: O(nd\u00b2) to compute X\u1d40X, O(d\u00b3) to invert. Practical limit: d \u2272 10,000. For larger d, use iterative methods (gradient descent). X\u1d40X must be invertible \u2014 fails with perfect multicollinearity (two features are exactly linearly dependent).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Geometric interpretation \u2014 OLS as orthogonal projection</span>\n    <p>The columns of X span a d-dimensional subspace of \u211d\u207f. The label vector y almost certainly does not lie in this subspace \u2014 no exact linear combination of your features equals y. OLS finds the point \u0177 in the column space of X closest to y \u2014 the orthogonal projection of y onto that subspace.<br><br>\n    The residuals (y \u2212 \u0177) are perpendicular (orthogonal) to the column space of X. This is exactly what X\u1d40(y \u2212 \u0177) = 0 means \u2014 the residuals are uncorrelated with every feature. This is why OLS residuals are always uncorrelated with the fitted values by construction.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LinearRegression\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> statsmodels.api <span class=\"k\">as</span> sm\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Normal equation \u2014 direct computation (numerically stable via lstsq)</span>\nX_b = np.c_[np.ones(len(X_train)), X_train]    <span class=\"c\"># add bias column</span>\nw_ols = np.linalg.lstsq(X_b, y_train, rcond=<span class=\"k\">None</span>)[<span class=\"y\">0</span>]\n<span class=\"c\"># lstsq uses SVD \u2014 safer than np.linalg.inv(X.T @ X) @ X.T @ y</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Direct inversion fails silently on near-singular X\u1d40X</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># sklearn for prediction</span>\nmodel = LinearRegression()\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)\ny_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># statsmodels for inference: p-values, confidence intervals, diagnostics</span>\nX_sm = sm.add_constant(X_train)\nols = sm.OLS(y_train, X_sm).fit()\nprint(ols.summary())   <span class=\"c\"># R\u00b2, adj-R\u00b2, F-stat, coefficient p-values, CIs</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. ASSUMPTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-assumptions\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>OLS Assumptions \u2014 LINE</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The four assumptions and their consequences when violated</span>\n    <p><strong>L \u2014 Linearity:</strong> E[y|X] = Xw. Violation \u2192 biased and inconsistent coefficient estimates. The model is wrong in a systematic direction.<br><br>\n    <strong>I \u2014 Independence of errors:</strong> errors are uncorrelated across observations. Critical for time series \u2014 autocorrelated residuals mean your standard errors are underestimated, making everything appear statistically significant when it isn't.<br><br>\n    <strong>N \u2014 Normality of residuals:</strong> needed for valid t-tests and confidence intervals on individual coefficients. The OLS coefficient estimates themselves are unbiased and consistent regardless of residual normality (Gauss-Markov theorem). CLT means normality holds approximately for large n. Matters least of the four.<br><br>\n    <strong>E \u2014 Equal variance (Homoscedasticity):</strong> Var(\u03b5|X) = \u03c3\u00b2 for all observations. Violation (heteroscedasticity) \u2192 OLS estimates are still unbiased but inefficient (not minimum variance). Standard errors are wrong \u2014 some coefficients appear significant when they aren't, and vice versa.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Which violations matter most in your work</span>\n    <p>For electricity demand forecasting: autocorrelation (violation of I) is almost certain \u2014 today's residual correlates with yesterday's. This doesn't bias your forecasts but it makes your standard errors meaningless. Use time-series-aware models or add lag features.<br><br>\n    Heteroscedasticity (violation of E) is common in demand data \u2014 variance is larger during peak periods than low-load periods. Fix: log-transform the target, which often stabilises variance. Or use weighted least squares, weighting low-load periods less.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> matplotlib.pyplot <span class=\"k\">as</span> plt\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> scipy.stats <span class=\"k\">as</span> stats\n\nresiduals = y_train - model.predict(X_train)\nfitted    = model.predict(X_train)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 1. Residuals vs Fitted \u2014 check linearity and homoscedasticity</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#    Should be random scatter around y=0, constant width</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#    Fan shape \u2192 heteroscedasticity. Curve \u2192 non-linearity.</span>\nplt.scatter(fitted, residuals, alpha=<span class=\"y\">0.4</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 2. Q-Q plot \u2014 check normality</span>\nstats.probplot(residuals, plot=plt)   <span class=\"c\"># points on diagonal = normal</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 3. Durbin-Watson \u2014 check autocorrelation (time series)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> statsmodels.stats.stattools <span class=\"k\">import</span> durbin_watson\ndw = durbin_watson(residuals)\n<span class=\"c\"># DW \u2248 2 \u2192 no autocorrelation. DW < 1.5 \u2192 positive autocorrelation.</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 4. VIF \u2014 check multicollinearity</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence <span class=\"k\">import</span> variance_inflation_factor\nvif = [variance_inflation_factor(X_train.values, i) <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(X_train.shape[<span class=\"y\">1</span>])]\n<span class=\"c\"># VIF > 10 \u2192 severe multicollinearity. Use Ridge or drop correlated features.</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. RIDGE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-ridge\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Ridge Regression \u2014 L2 Regularisation</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>Ridge adds an L2 penalty to OLS: minimise ||y \u2212 Xw||\u00b2 + \u03bb\u03a3w\u1d62\u00b2.<br><br>\n    Closed-form solution: <strong>w_ridge = (X\u1d40X + \u03bbI)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y</strong>.<br><br>\n    Adding \u03bbI to X\u1d40X makes the matrix strictly positive definite and therefore always invertible \u2014 even when features are perfectly correlated (X\u1d40X is singular). This is why Ridge handles multicollinearity where OLS fails. As \u03bb\u21920, Ridge \u2192 OLS. As \u03bb\u2192\u221e, all weights \u2192 0 (predict the mean).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">When Ridge matters most \u2014 correlated features</span>\n    <p>In OLS with two perfectly correlated features (temperature_C and temperature_F), there are infinitely many weight combinations that give the same prediction. OLS picks one arbitrarily and the coefficients are numerically unstable \u2014 change one training point and the coefficients change dramatically. Ridge distributes the weight stably across both correlated features, producing stable, interpretable coefficients.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. LASSO \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-lasso\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Lasso Regression \u2014 L1 Regularisation</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>Lasso adds an L1 penalty: minimise ||y \u2212 Xw||\u00b2 + \u03bb\u03a3|w\u1d62|. No closed-form solution \u2014 requires coordinate descent or subgradient methods. The L1 penalty has a constant gradient (\u03bb\u00b7sign(w)) regardless of weight size \u2014 this constant push drives weights all the way to zero, performing automatic feature selection.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Lasso is unstable with correlated features</span>\n    <p>If features A and B are highly correlated, Lasso will zero out one and keep the other, but which is arbitrary. Different random seeds or slightly different training samples may select A one time, B the next. If you need stable feature selection from a correlated set: use Elastic Net, or use stability selection (run Lasso many times on bootstrap samples and keep features that appear consistently).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> Ridge, Lasso, ElasticNet, LassoCV\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Ridge: always use CV to find alpha</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> RidgeCV\nridge = RidgeCV(alphas=[<span class=\"y\">0.01</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>, <span class=\"y\">100</span>, <span class=\"y\">1000</span>], cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\nridge.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Ridge best \u03b1: {ridge.alpha_}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"All coefs non-zero: {(ridge.coef_ == 0).sum()}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># should be 0</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Lasso: feature selection</span>\nlasso = LassoCV(cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, max_iter=<span class=\"y\">5000</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nlasso.fit(X_train, y_train)\nselected = X.columns[lasso.coef_ != <span class=\"y\">0</span>]\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Lasso selected {len(selected)}/{X.shape[1]} features: {list(selected)}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Elastic Net: correlated features + sparsity needed</span>\nenet = ElasticNet(alpha=<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, l1_ratio=<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># l1_ratio: 0=Ridge, 1=Lasso</span>\nenet.fit(X_train, y_train)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. POLYNOMIAL \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-poly\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Polynomial Regression</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 non-linearity via feature expansion</span>\n    <p>Polynomial regression is linear regression applied to an expanded feature set that includes polynomial terms (x\u00b2, x\u00b3, x\u1d62x\u2c7c interaction terms). The model is still linear in the parameters \u2014 only the features are non-linear. This means all OLS theory still applies. The expanded features are created with PolynomialFeatures before fitting LinearRegression.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Polynomial regression overfits aggressively at high degree</span>\n    <p>Degree 2 on 10 features = 66 features. Degree 3 = 286 features. Degree 5 = 3,003 features. Feature explosion makes overfitting almost guaranteed without aggressive regularisation. In practice: polynomial regression rarely used beyond degree 2. For complex non-linear patterns, tree-based models or neural nets are almost always better and don't require explicit feature engineering of interactions.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> PolynomialFeatures\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> Ridge\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Polynomial features + Ridge to control overfitting</span>\npoly_ridge = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'poly'</span>,  PolynomialFeatures(degree=<span class=\"y\">2</span>, include_bias=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)),\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scale'</span>, RobustScaler()),         <span class=\"c\"># polynomial features are skewed</span>\n    (<span class=\"g\">'model'</span>, Ridge(alpha=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>))        <span class=\"c\"># always regularise polynomial models</span>\n])\npoly_ridge.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Degree-2 features: {poly_ridge.named_steps['poly'].n_output_features_}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"reg-qa\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the normal equation? When would you not use it?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">w = (X\u1d40X)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y \u2014 the closed-form OLS solution, derived by setting the gradient of the squared loss to zero. Don't use when: (1) d &gt; ~10K \u2014 matrix inversion is O(d\u00b3), becomes too slow. Use gradient descent instead. (2) Features are perfectly correlated \u2014 X\u1d40X is singular, inversion fails. Ridge regression fixes this by adding \u03bbI: w = (X\u1d40X + \u03bbI)\u207b\u00b9X\u1d40y. (3) Data doesn't fit in memory \u2014 mini-batch gradient descent handles streaming data. In practice, sklearn's LinearRegression uses SVD-based least squares (lstsq), which is more numerically stable than direct inversion and handles near-singular cases gracefully.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What are the OLS assumptions and which violations matter most in practice?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">LINE: Linearity, Independence, Normality, Equal variance (homoscedasticity). Linearity violations cause biased estimates \u2014 the model is systematically wrong. Fix: add polynomial features or switch to non-linear models. Independence violations (autocorrelated errors in time series) don't bias the coefficient estimates but make standard errors wrong \u2014 everything appears more statistically significant than it is. Fix: add lag features, use time-series models, or correct standard errors with Newey-West. Homoscedasticity violations (variance of errors varies with X) also produce wrong standard errors. Fix: log-transform the target for right-skewed outcomes, or use weighted least squares. Normality of residuals matters least \u2014 OLS coefficients are unbiased and consistent without it. Only affects the validity of t-tests on individual coefficients, and CLT makes this approximately satisfied for large n.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Ridge vs Lasso \u2014 when do you choose each?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Ridge when: all features are potentially relevant and you want stable coefficient estimates, especially with correlated features. Ridge distributes weight across correlated features stably. No feature selection. Lasso when: you believe most features are irrelevant and want automatic feature selection. L1 drives some weights to exactly zero. Unstable with correlated features \u2014 picks one arbitrarily. Elastic Net when: you have many correlated features where many are irrelevant. Gets sparsity from L1 and stability from L2. Always cross-validate the regularisation strength (RidgeCV, LassoCV). Never eyeball \u03bb.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_classification": "<main>\n  <h1>Classification Algorithms</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Logistic Regression</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Probabilistic view, log-odds, MLE, odds ratio</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">KNN</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Distance-based, curse of dimensionality, inference cost</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">SVM</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Maximum margin, support vectors, kernel trick</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Naive Bayes</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Bayes theorem, conditional independence, text</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">When to use each</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Decision guide \u2014 and why GBM still usually wins</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Logistic regression coefficient interpretation:</strong> coefficient w\u2c7c means a one-unit increase in feature j multiplies the odds by e^w\u2c7c \u2014 this is an odds ratio, not a probability effect. The effect on probability depends on where you are on the sigmoid: near P=0.5 (steep region) a small change has a large probability effect; near P=0.01 a large change has almost no probability effect. Never say \"feature j increases probability by w\u2c7c.\"</li>\n    <li><strong>Logistic regression is a linear classifier:</strong> decision boundary where P(y=1|x)=0.5 means \u03c3(w\u1d40x)=0.5 means w\u1d40x=0 \u2014 a hyperplane. Cannot learn XOR, circles, or spirals in the original feature space. If the boundary needs to be non-linear: add polynomial features first, or switch to a tree-based model or SVM with RBF kernel.</li>\n    <li><strong>KNN and the curse of dimensionality:</strong> in high-dimensional space, all points become approximately equidistant. The ratio of nearest-to-farthest neighbour distance approaches 1 as dimensions increase \u2014 \"nearest\" becomes meaningless. KNN degrades above ~20 features. Apply PCA first, and always scale features \u2014 a feature with range [0,10000] completely dominates distances over one with range [0,1].</li>\n    <li><strong>SVM scaling failure:</strong> training SVM solves a quadratic program: O(n\u00b2) to O(n\u00b3). For n &gt; 100K rows, impractical. Use LinearSVC (primal formulation, O(n\u00b7d)) for large datasets needing a linear boundary. RBF-kernel SVM is valuable for medium datasets (&lt;50K rows) with genuinely non-linear structure that can't be captured by feature engineering.</li>\n    <li><strong>Naive Bayes works despite wrong assumptions:</strong> the independence assumption is almost always violated in real data. It still works because: for classification we only need the correct ranking between classes, not accurate probabilities; errors in individual conditional probability estimates often cancel across many features; and with limited data the independence assumption acts as regularisation. Competitive for text classification where you have many binary/count features.</li>\n    <li><strong>None of these beat gradient boosting on tabular data:</strong> know logistic regression, KNN, SVM, and Naive Bayes for interviews. In production: start with logistic regression (fast, explainable baseline), then LightGBM if you need more accuracy. SVM and KNN almost never win on tabular data at scale.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. LOGISTIC REGRESSION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-logreg\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Logistic Regression</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the probabilistic formulation</span>\n    <p>Logistic regression models the probability of the positive class as:<br><br>\n    <strong>P(y=1|x) = \u03c3(w\u1d40x + b)</strong> where \u03c3(z) = 1/(1+e\u207b\u1dbb)<br><br>\n    Equivalently in log-odds (logit) form:<br>\n    <strong>log[P(y=1)/P(y=0)] = w\u1d40x + b</strong><br><br>\n    This is a linear model in log-odds space. The word \"logistic\" comes from the logistic (sigmoid) function mapping log-odds to probability.<br><br>\n    Training: minimise negative log-likelihood = cross-entropy:<br>\n    L = \u2212\u03a3[y\u1d62log(\u0177\u1d62) + (1\u2212y\u1d62)log(1\u2212\u0177\u1d62)]<br><br>\n    No closed-form solution \u2014 trained with gradient descent (lbfgs, liblinear, saga). The MLE connection: minimising cross-entropy is equivalent to maximising the likelihood of the training labels under the model's predicted probabilities.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why logistic regression is a linear classifier</span>\n    <p>The decision boundary is where P(y=1|x) = 0.5 \u2192 \u03c3(w\u1d40x) = 0.5 \u2192 w\u1d40x = 0. This is a hyperplane \u2014 a linear boundary in feature space. Logistic regression cannot learn a circle, a spiral, or any non-linear shape in the original features. Two solutions: (1) add polynomial/interaction features first (feature engineering), (2) switch to a non-linear model (tree, SVM with kernel, neural net).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Coefficient interpretation \u2014 not what it looks like</span>\n    <p>Coefficient w\u2c7c means: a one-unit increase in feature j increases log-odds by w\u2c7c, which multiplies odds by e^w\u2c7c. This is an odds ratio \u2014 NOT a probability effect. The effect on probability depends on where you are on the sigmoid: near P=0.5 (steep part), a small feature change has large probability effect; near P=0.01, the same change has almost no probability effect. Never say \"feature j increases the probability by w\u2c7c\" \u2014 it's wrong. Say \"multiplies the odds by e^w\u2c7c.\"</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.linear_model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LogisticRegression\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> roc_auc_score, log_loss\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\nmodel = LogisticRegression(\n    C=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>,              <span class=\"c\"># C = 1/\u03bb \u2014 higher C = less regularisation</span>\n    penalty=<span class=\"g\">'l2'</span>,       <span class=\"c\"># l2 default; l1 for feature selection (use solver='liblinear')</span>\n    solver=<span class=\"g\">'lbfgs'</span>,     <span class=\"c\"># for l2; saga for l1/elasticnet or large datasets</span>\n    class_weight=<span class=\"g\">'balanced'</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># handles class imbalance</span>\n    max_iter=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>\n)\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Probabilities \u2014 always use these, not binary predictions</span>\ny_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, <span class=\"y\">1</span>]\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"AUC-ROC: {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob):.4f}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Log-loss: {log_loss(y_test, y_prob):.4f}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Coefficient interpretation: odds ratios</span>\nodds_ratios = np.exp(model.coef_[<span class=\"y\">0</span>])\n<span class=\"c\"># odds_ratios[j] > 1 \u2192 feature j increases odds of y=1</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># odds_ratios[j] < 1 \u2192 feature j decreases odds of y=1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Threshold: default 0.5 is almost always wrong for imbalanced data</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> precision_recall_curve\nprec, rec, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_prob)\n<span class=\"c\"># Choose threshold that meets your business requirement (e.g., recall \u2265 0.9)</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. KNN \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-knn\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>K-Nearest Neighbours</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition</span>\n    <p>KNN makes predictions using the K training examples closest to the query point by distance (Euclidean, cosine, or Manhattan). For classification: majority vote of K neighbours. For regression: average of K neighbours. No training phase \u2014 all computation deferred to inference. This is a <strong>lazy learner</strong>: memorises the entire training set, computes distance to all n points at prediction time. Complexity: O(nd) per prediction for brute force. KD-trees or Ball trees reduce this to O(d\u00b7log(n)) for low-dimensional data.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Curse of dimensionality \u2014 KNN fails above ~20 features</span>\n    <p>In high-dimensional space, all points become approximately equidistant from each other. The ratio of the distance to the nearest vs. farthest neighbour approaches 1 as d increases \u2014 \"nearest\" becomes meaningless. With 100 features, your 5 \"nearest\" neighbours may be almost as far away as random points. KNN degrades catastrophically above ~20 dimensions. Always apply PCA or feature selection before using KNN on high-dimensional data. Also: KNN requires feature scaling \u2014 a feature with range [0, 10000] completely dominates distances over one with range [0, 1].</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.neighbors <span class=\"k\">import</span> KNeighborsClassifier\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> StandardScaler\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> cross_val_score\n\n<span class=\"c\"># KNN always needs scaling \u2014 use Pipeline to prevent leakage</span>\npipe = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, StandardScaler()),\n    (<span class=\"g\">'knn'</span>,    KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, metric=<span class=\"g\">'euclidean'</span>))\n])\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Tune K via cross-validation</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> k <span class=\"k\">in</span> [<span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>, <span class=\"y\">7</span>, <span class=\"y\">11</span>, <span class=\"y\">15</span>, <span class=\"y\">21</span>]:\n    pipe.set_params(knn__n_neighbors=k)\n    score = cross_val_score(pipe, X, y, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>).mean()\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"K={k}: AUC={score:.4f}\"</span>)\n<span class=\"c\"># Low K \u2192 high variance (complex boundary). High K \u2192 high bias (smooth boundary).</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. SVM \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-svm\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Support Vector Machine</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 maximum margin and the kernel trick</span>\n    <p>SVM finds the hyperplane that maximises the margin between classes. <strong>Margin = 2/||w||</strong>. Maximising margin = minimising ||w||. The support vectors are the training points closest to the decision boundary \u2014 only these determine the hyperplane. All other points can be removed without changing the solution.<br><br>\n    <strong>Soft-margin SVM</strong> (parameter C): allows some misclassifications. <strong>High C</strong> = small margin, fit training data tightly (can overfit). <strong>Low C</strong> = large margin, accept more training errors (better generalisation).<br><br>\n    <strong>Kernel trick:</strong> maps features to a higher-dimensional space implicitly via a kernel function K(x\u1d62, x\u2c7c) = \u03c6(x\u1d62)\u00b7\u03c6(x\u2c7c). The SVM only needs inner products \u2014 the kernel computes \u03c6(x\u1d62)\u00b7\u03c6(x\u2c7c) without computing \u03c6(x) explicitly. RBF kernel: K(x\u1d62, x\u2c7c) = exp(\u2212\u03b3||x\u1d62\u2212x\u2c7c||\u00b2). Allows non-linear boundaries in the original space.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">SVM does not scale to large datasets</span>\n    <p>Training SVM solves a quadratic programming problem: O(n\u00b2) to O(n\u00b3). For n &gt; 100K, impractical. For large datasets: use LinearSVC (solves the primal, O(n\u00b7d), no kernel) when you only need a linear boundary. Or use logistic regression \u2014 it's almost always faster and nearly as accurate for linear boundaries. SVM with RBF kernel is most valuable for medium datasets (&lt;50K rows) with genuinely non-linear structure that can't be captured by feature engineering.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.svm <span class=\"k\">import</span> SVC, LinearSVC\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n\n<span class=\"c\"># SVM needs scaling \u2014 critical for kernel methods</span>\nsvm_pipe = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, StandardScaler()),\n    (<span class=\"g\">'svm'</span>,    SVC(kernel=<span class=\"g\">'rbf'</span>, C=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>, gamma=<span class=\"g\">'scale'</span>, probability=<span class=\"y\">True</span>))\n    <span class=\"c\"># probability=True: enables predict_proba (uses Platt scaling \u2014 slow)</span>\n    <span class=\"c\"># gamma='scale': \u03b3 = 1/(n_features \u00d7 Var(X)) \u2014 sensible default</span>\n])\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Large dataset: LinearSVC (primal formulation, much faster)</span>\nlinear_svm = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, StandardScaler()),\n    (<span class=\"g\">'svm'</span>,    LinearSVC(C=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>, max_iter=<span class=\"y\">5000</span>))\n])\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Grid search over C and gamma for RBF kernel</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> GridSearchCV\nparam_grid = {<span class=\"g\">'svm__C'</span>: [<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>, <span class=\"y\">100</span>], <span class=\"g\">'svm__gamma'</span>: [<span class=\"g\">'scale'</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.01</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.001</span>]}\ngrid = GridSearchCV(svm_pipe, param_grid, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, scoring=<span class=\"g\">'roc_auc'</span>)\ngrid.fit(X_train, y_train)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. NAIVE BAYES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-nb\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Naive Bayes</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Bayes theorem + independence assumption</span>\n    <p>Naive Bayes classifies using Bayes' theorem:<br>\n    <strong>P(y|x) \u221d P(y) \u00b7 \u03a0 P(x\u1d62|y)</strong><br><br>\n    The \"naive\" assumption: all features x\u1d62 are conditionally independent given y. Under this assumption, the joint likelihood factors into a product \u2014 tractable to compute. This assumption is almost always violated in real data. Despite this, Naive Bayes often performs well in practice because:<br>\n    \u2014 For classification, we only need the correct ranking of classes, not accurate probabilities<br>\n    \u2014 With limited data, the independence assumption acts as regularisation<br>\n    \u2014 Errors in individual P(x\u1d62|y) estimates often cancel across many features<br><br>\n    <strong>Gaussian NB:</strong> P(x\u1d62|y) modelled as Gaussian \u2014 for continuous features.<br>\n    <strong>Multinomial NB:</strong> P(x\u1d62|y) modelled as multinomial \u2014 for word counts in text.<br>\n    <strong>Bernoulli NB:</strong> P(x\u1d62|y) modelled as Bernoulli \u2014 for binary features (word present/absent).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why Naive Bayes works for text \u2014 the bag-of-words match</span>\n    <p>In text classification, the \"independence of words given class\" assumption is more defensible than it sounds. Yes, \"machine\" and \"learning\" are correlated. But given a class (\"ML paper\"), the conditional independence assumption \u2014 that each word's frequency given the class is independent of other words \u2014 is a reasonable approximation. Naive Bayes with TF-IDF features is a strong text classification baseline that often beats logistic regression on small datasets because it needs fewer examples to estimate parameters reliably.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. WHEN TO USE EACH \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-which\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>When to Use Each</h2>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Algorithm</th><th>Wins when</th><th>Fails when</th><th>Typical use</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Logistic Regression</td><td>Linear boundary OK, need explainability, fast training, probability calibration needed</td><td>Non-linear patterns, many interactions</td><td>Baseline + production explainable model</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>KNN</td><td>Very complex boundary, small &lt;10K dataset, non-parametric needed</td><td>High dimensions, large datasets, slow inference</td><td>Rarely in production; useful in recommendation systems</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>SVM (RBF)</td><td>Medium dataset (&lt;50K), clear margin exists, non-linear boundary</td><td>Large datasets, need calibrated probabilities, many features</td><td>Image classification (pre-deep learning), bioinformatics</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Naive Bayes</td><td>Text classification, very small dataset, need speed</td><td>Continuous features with interactions, need precision</td><td>Spam filters, text categorisation, NLP pipeline component</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>LightGBM/XGBoost</td><td>Tabular data, medium-large dataset, highest accuracy needed</td><td>When you need a strict linear model for regulatory reasons</td><td>Almost all production tabular classification</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"clf-qa\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What does a logistic regression coefficient actually mean?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Logistic regression models log-odds = w\u1d40x. Coefficient w\u2c7c means a one-unit increase in feature j increases the log-odds by w\u2c7c, which multiplies the odds ratio by e^w\u2c7c. If w\u2c7c = 0.7, then e^0.7 \u2248 2.01 \u2014 one unit increase in feature j approximately doubles the odds of y=1. This is NOT a probability effect. The effect on probability depends on where you are on the sigmoid: near P=0.5 it's large, near P=0.01 it's tiny. When reporting to stakeholders: \"a one-unit increase in [feature] is associated with a 2\u00d7 increase in the odds of [outcome].\"</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the kernel trick in SVM and why does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The kernel trick allows SVM to find non-linear decision boundaries without explicitly computing the transformation to a higher-dimensional space. SVM's decision function depends only on inner products between data points: \u03c6(x\u1d62)\u00b7\u03c6(x\u2c7c). The kernel function K(x\u1d62, x\u2c7c) computes this inner product in the transformed space without computing \u03c6(x) explicitly. The RBF kernel K(x\u1d62, x\u2c7c) = exp(\u2212\u03b3||x\u1d62\u2212x\u2c7c||\u00b2) corresponds to an infinite-dimensional feature space \u2014 you get a non-linear boundary without any explicit feature engineering. Why it matters: you can learn complex boundaries while only needing to compute pairwise distances in the original space \u2014 computationally tractable for small-medium datasets.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does Naive Bayes work despite its independence assumption being wrong?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Three reasons: (1) For classification, we only need P(y=1|x) &gt; P(y=0|x) \u2014 the correct ranking, not accurate probabilities. Even if individual P(x\u1d62|y) estimates are wrong, the classifier is correct as long as the ranking is preserved. (2) Errors in individual conditional probability estimates often partially cancel across many features. (3) With small training sets, the independence assumption acts as regularisation \u2014 it prevents overfitting by not learning the complex correlations that might be noise. Naive Bayes is particularly effective for text classification where you have many binary/count features (words), limited labelled data, and the class-conditional word distributions are what differentiate classes.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_trees": "<main>\n  <h1>Tree-Based Models</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Decision Trees</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Gini, entropy, split criterion, pruning</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Random Forest</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why bagging works \u2014 the math</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Gradient Boosting</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Residual fitting \u2014 second-order view</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">XGBoost</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Second-order gradients, regularisation, speed</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">LightGBM</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Histogram binning, GOSS, leaf-wise growth</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">CatBoost</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Ordered boosting \u2014 why it prevents leakage</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Production concerns</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Custom loss, monotone constraints, imbalance</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Feature Importance</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Split vs gain vs permutation vs SHAP</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Decision tree split:</strong> find (feature, threshold) that maximises information gain = parent impurity \u2212 weighted child impurities. Gini = 1 \u2212 \u03a3p\u1d62\u00b2. Entropy = \u2212\u03a3p\u1d62log\u2082(p\u1d62). Both work similarly in practice.</li>\n      <li><strong>Why bagging reduces variance:</strong> Var(mean of n iid vars) = \u03c3\u00b2/n. Trees aren't iid (trained on correlated data), so the reduction is less, but bootstrap + feature subsampling decorrelates them. Bias stays roughly the same \u2014 you're averaging many low-bias trees.</li>\n      <li><strong>Gradient boosting:</strong> each tree fits pseudo-residuals = \u2212\u2202L/\u2202\u0177. For MSE loss, this is exactly y \u2212 \u0177 (actual residuals). For other losses, the residuals are the negative gradient \u2014 hence the name.</li>\n      <li><strong>XGBoost improvement:</strong> uses second-order Taylor expansion of loss \u2014 both gradient g\u1d62 and Hessian h\u1d62. This gives a more accurate approximation and allows solving for optimal leaf weights analytically.</li>\n      <li><strong>LightGBM speed:</strong> histogram binning reduces split candidates from O(n_unique) to O(256). GOSS keeps all high-gradient samples, drops most low-gradient ones. Leaf-wise growth \u2260 level-wise \u2014 finds the globally best split at each step.</li>\n      <li><strong>CatBoost ordered boosting:</strong> residuals computed using only trees built before each observation's \"time\" \u2014 prevents the subtle leakage in standard boosting where your own label influences your residual.</li>\n      <li><strong>scale_pos_weight in XGBoost:</strong> set to sum(negative) / sum(positive). Equivalent to class_weight='balanced'. Use for imbalanced targets, not if you care about calibrated probabilities.</li>\n      <li><strong>Monotone constraints:</strong> force model to be monotonically increasing/decreasing in a feature. Critical for demand forecasting (demand can't decrease as temperature increases past a threshold), pricing, risk models.</li>\n      <li><strong>SHAP values:</strong> fairly allocate prediction credit across features using Shapley values from game theory. Additive: SHAP values sum to prediction \u2212 base value. Accounts for feature interactions. Permutation importance does not.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. DECISION TREES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-dt\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Decision Trees</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 split criterion and information gain</span>\n    <p>A decision tree partitions the feature space into rectangular regions by recursively splitting on (feature, threshold) pairs. At each node, it tries every feature and every threshold, choosing the split that maximises information gain:<br><br>\n    <strong>IG = Impurity(parent) \u2212 [|L|/n \u00b7 Impurity(L) + |R|/n \u00b7 Impurity(R)]</strong><br><br>\n    <strong>Gini impurity:</strong> G = 1 \u2212 \u03a3p\u1d62\u00b2 (probability each sample is misclassified if labelled randomly using class distribution at that node). G=0 is pure. G=0.5 is maximally impure.<br>\n    <strong>Entropy:</strong> H = \u2212\u03a3p\u1d62log\u2082(p\u1d62). Information-theoretic impurity. Slightly more expensive to compute, similar results in practice.<br>\n    For regression: minimises variance or MAE of the target in each resulting node.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Pruning \u2014 controlling complexity</span>\n    <p><strong>Pre-pruning (early stopping):</strong> stop splitting when max_depth is reached, node has fewer than min_samples_split, or the best split gain is below a threshold. Simple and fast.<br><br>\n    <strong>Cost-complexity pruning (post-pruning):</strong> grow the full tree, then prune bottom-up. Each subtree T has a cost: Error(T) + \u03b1\u00b7|T| where |T| is the number of leaves and \u03b1 is the complexity parameter. As \u03b1 increases, more pruning occurs. Cross-validate \u03b1 to find the best value. sklearn's <code>ccp_alpha</code> implements this. More principled than pre-pruning but more expensive.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Decision trees overfit aggressively without constraints</span>\n    <p>An unconstrained decision tree will grow until every leaf contains exactly one training sample \u2014 zero training error, useless generalisation. Always set at least one of: <code>max_depth</code>, <code>min_samples_leaf</code>, <code>min_impurity_decrease</code>, or <code>ccp_alpha</code>. A depth-1 tree (decision stump) is a useful interpretable baseline. In production, decision trees alone are rarely used \u2014 they're the building block for ensembles.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.tree <span class=\"k\">import</span> DecisionTreeClassifier\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.model_selection <span class=\"k\">import</span> cross_val_score\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Cost-complexity pruning: find optimal ccp_alpha</span>\ntree_full = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\npath = tree_full.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)\nccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas[:-<span class=\"y\">1</span>]   <span class=\"c\"># last alpha prunes to root, ignore it</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Cross-validate each alpha</span>\nscores = []\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> alpha <span class=\"k\">in</span> ccp_alphas:\n    tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=alpha, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\n    cv_scores = cross_val_score(tree, X_train, y_train, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\n    scores.append(cv_scores.mean())\n\nbest_alpha = ccp_alphas[scores.index(max(scores))]\ntree_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=best_alpha, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\ntree_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. RANDOM FOREST \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-rf\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Random Forest \u2014 why bagging works mathematically</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the variance reduction proof</span>\n    <p>For n independent identically distributed random variables each with variance \u03c3\u00b2, their mean has variance \u03c3\u00b2/n. Individual decision trees have low bias (fully grown) but high variance \u2014 each responds dramatically to different training data.<br><br>\n    Trees trained on bootstrap samples of the same dataset are not independent \u2014 they're trained on correlated data. Let \u03c1 be the pairwise correlation between tree predictions. Then:<br><br>\n    <strong>Var(average of n trees) = \u03c1\u03c3\u00b2 + (1\u2212\u03c1)\u03c3\u00b2/n</strong><br><br>\n    As n\u2192\u221e, the second term vanishes, leaving \u03c1\u03c3\u00b2. The irreducible floor on variance is determined by how correlated the trees are. Feature subsampling (\u221ad features per split) reduces \u03c1 by forcing different trees to find different split features. This is why the feature subsampling is essential \u2014 more trees beyond ~300 adds diminishing returns, but low \u03c1 is always valuable.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 why a panel of diverse judges beats one judge</span>\n    <p>One judge's verdict can be wrong in a systematic way \u2014 every case involving a certain demographic, they rule the same direction. 100 judges who all trained at the same school and share the same biases: their average verdict is still wrong in the same systematic way \u2014 correlation means averaging doesn't help. 100 judges with genuinely different backgrounds, different case histories, different areas of expertise: their individual errors are uncorrelated, and averaging cancels individual errors.<br><br>\n    Bootstrap sampling makes each tree see different training examples. Feature subsampling forces different split features at each node. Together, they break the correlation \u03c1. The formula says: reducing \u03c1 reduces the variance floor more than simply adding more trees.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">OOB score is not a substitute for cross-validation</span>\n    <p>Out-of-bag samples (~37% of data not in each bootstrap) give a free validation estimate. But OOB estimates can be optimistic for small datasets (the OOB sets overlap across trees) and don't account for preprocessing fitted inside a pipeline. Use OOB as a cheap sanity check, not as your final model selection criterion.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.ensemble <span class=\"k\">import</span> RandomForestClassifier\n\nrf = RandomForestClassifier(\n    n_estimators=<span class=\"y\">500</span>,       <span class=\"c\"># variance reduction plateaus around 300-500</span>\n    max_features=<span class=\"g\">'sqrt'</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># key for decorrelation: \u221ad features per split</span>\n    max_depth=<span class=\"k\">None</span>,         <span class=\"c\"># fully grown: low bias, high per-tree variance</span>\n    min_samples_leaf=<span class=\"y\">1</span>,     <span class=\"c\"># increase to 5-20 for noisy data</span>\n    bootstrap=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,         <span class=\"c\"># sample with replacement</span>\n    oob_score=<span class=\"y\">True</span>,         <span class=\"c\"># free validation estimate</span>\n    class_weight=<span class=\"g\">'balanced'</span>, <span class=\"c\"># handles imbalanced targets</span>\n    n_jobs=-<span class=\"y\">1</span>,              <span class=\"c\"># trees are independent \u2014 fully parallelisable</span>\n    random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\nrf.fit(X_train, y_train)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"OOB score: {rf.oob_score_:.4f}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># sanity check only</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. GRADIENT BOOSTING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-gb\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Gradient Boosting \u2014 the second-order view</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 gradient boosting as functional gradient descent</span>\n    <p>Gradient boosting builds an additive model F(x) = \u03a3 \u03b1\u2098h\u2098(x) where each h\u2098 is a decision tree. At step m, the new tree h\u2098 is fit to the <strong>negative gradient</strong> of the loss w.r.t. the current prediction:<br><br>\n    <strong>r\u1d62\u2098 = \u2212[\u2202L(y\u1d62, F(x\u1d62)) / \u2202F(x\u1d62)]</strong><br><br>\n    For MSE loss: \u2202(y\u2212F)\u00b2/\u2202F = \u22122(y\u2212F), so r\u1d62 = y \u2212 F(x\u1d62) \u2014 exactly the residuals. For other losses (log-loss, MAE), the \"pseudo-residuals\" are not the actual residuals but the negative gradient of the specific loss. This is the gradient descent interpretation: each tree is a step in function space to reduce the loss.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Gradient boosting amplifies noise \u2014 early stopping is mandatory in production</span>\n    <p>Every iteration, the model specifically targets current errors. Errors from real patterns \u2192 good. Errors from noise \u2192 the model starts fitting noise. After enough trees, training loss keeps falling while validation loss rises \u2014 classic overfitting. The fix: monitor validation loss and stop adding trees when it plateaus. In XGBoost/LightGBM: <code>early_stopping_rounds=50</code>. In sklearn GBM: use <code>n_iter_no_change</code>. Never use a fixed n_estimators without early stopping in production.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. XGBOOST \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-xgb\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>XGBoost \u2014 second-order gradients</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the second-order Taylor expansion</span>\n    <p>Standard GBM uses only the first-order gradient (direction). XGBoost uses a second-order Taylor expansion of the loss at each step:<br><br>\n    L(y, F+h) \u2248 L(y, F) + g\u1d62h + \u00bdh\u1d62h\u00b2<br><br>\n    where g\u1d62 = \u2202L/\u2202F (gradient) and h\u1d62 = \u2202\u00b2L/\u2202F\u00b2 (Hessian). This provides curvature information \u2014 how fast the gradient is changing. With this, the optimal weight for a leaf with instances I is:<br><br>\n    <strong>w* = \u2212\u03a3\u1d62G\u1d62 / (\u03a3\u1d62H\u1d62 + \u03bb)</strong><br><br>\n    And the score for a split is: \u00bd[G\u00b2L/(HL+\u03bb) + G\u00b2R/(HR+\u03bb) \u2212 G\u00b2/(H+\u03bb)] \u2212 \u03b3 (where \u03bb is L2 regularisation, \u03b3 is the minimum gain required to split). Everything is solved analytically per leaf \u2014 no gradient descent inside the tree.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> xgboost <span class=\"k\">as</span> xgb\n\nmodel = xgb.XGBClassifier(\n    n_estimators=<span class=\"y\">2000</span>,      <span class=\"c\"># use with early stopping</span>\n    learning_rate=<span class=\"y\">0.05</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># lower = better generalisation (set lr first, then tune rest)</span>\n    max_depth=<span class=\"y\">6</span>,            <span class=\"c\"># 3-8 typical; depth controls feature interactions</span>\n    subsample=<span class=\"y\">0.8</span>,          <span class=\"c\"># row subsampling per tree</span>\n    colsample_bytree=<span class=\"y\">0.8</span>,   <span class=\"c\"># column subsampling per tree</span>\n    colsample_bylevel=<span class=\"y\">0.8</span>,  <span class=\"c\"># column subsampling per level (additional)</span>\n    reg_alpha=<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>,          <span class=\"c\"># L1 on leaf weights (sparsity)</span>\n    reg_lambda=<span class=\"y\">1.0</span>,         <span class=\"c\"># L2 on leaf weights (shrinkage)</span>\n    min_child_weight=<span class=\"y\">5</span>,     <span class=\"c\"># min \u03a3Hessian in a leaf \u2014 controls overfitting</span>\n    <span class=\"c\"># Class imbalance:</span>\n    scale_pos_weight=<span class=\"y\">9</span>,     <span class=\"c\"># sum(negative)/sum(positive) \u2014 use when target is imbalanced</span>\n    <span class=\"c\"># eval_metric='aucpr',  # AUC-PR better than AUC-ROC for imbalanced</span>\n    early_stopping_rounds=<span class=\"y\">50</span>,\n    random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)], verbose=<span class=\"y\">200</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Monotone constraints \u2014 critical for forecasting and risk models</span>\nmodel_mono = xgb.XGBRegressor(\n    monotone_constraints={\n        <span class=\"g\">'temperature'</span>: <span class=\"y\">1</span>,    <span class=\"c\"># demand must increase with temperature (cooling load)</span>\n        <span class=\"g\">'hour'</span>: <span class=\"y\">0</span>,           <span class=\"c\"># no monotone constraint on hour</span>\n        <span class=\"g\">'holiday'</span>: -<span class=\"y\">1</span>,       <span class=\"c\"># demand must decrease on holidays</span>\n    }\n)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. LIGHTGBM \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-lgb\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>LightGBM \u2014 three speed innovations</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 histogram binning, GOSS, EFB</span>\n    <p><strong>Histogram binning:</strong> continuous features bucketed into 256 bins. Finding the best split is O(256) per feature instead of O(n_unique) \u2014 1000\u00d7 faster for high-cardinality features. Slight accuracy loss from discretisation, minimal in practice.<br><br>\n    <strong>GOSS (Gradient-based One-Side Sampling):</strong> keep all instances with large gradients (large errors \u2014 informative, need fixing). Randomly sample a fraction of small-gradient instances (already well fit \u2014 less informative). Result: fewer samples per tree without losing the most informative ones. Typically 80-90% data reduction with &lt;1% accuracy loss.<br><br>\n    <strong>EFB (Exclusive Feature Bundling):</strong> features that are mutually exclusive (rarely non-zero simultaneously \u2014 common in one-hot encoded categoricals) are bundled into one feature. Reduces effective feature count.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Leaf-wise vs level-wise growth</span>\n    <p>XGBoost grows trees level-by-level \u2014 all nodes at depth d are split before any node at depth d+1. LightGBM grows leaf-wise \u2014 at each step, it finds the globally best leaf to split regardless of which level it's on. This produces more asymmetric, deeper trees and often achieves lower loss with fewer leaves. The trade-off: leaf-wise growth can produce very deep branches that overfit small datasets. <code>num_leaves</code> is the primary complexity control in LightGBM, not <code>max_depth</code>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">LightGBM on small data (&lt;10K rows) \u2014 leaf-wise overfits badly</span>\n    <p>On small datasets, leaf-wise growth finds splits that perfectly fit the training data without generalising. Aggressive mitigations: set <code>num_leaves=15-31</code> (not the default 31 when data is very small), set <code>min_child_samples=30+</code>, and increase <code>reg_lambda</code>. Alternatively, just use XGBoost with its level-wise growth on small data \u2014 less tuning needed.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> lightgbm <span class=\"k\">as</span> lgb\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Custom loss in LightGBM: return gradient and Hessian</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">mape_loss</span>(y_true, y_pred):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Custom MAPE loss for load forecasting.\"\"\"</span>\n    grad = (y_pred - y_true) / (y_true * <span class=\"k\">abs</span>(y_true) + <span class=\"y\">1e-8</span>)\n    hess = <span class=\"y\">1</span> / (<span class=\"k\">abs</span>(y_true) + <span class=\"y\">1e-8</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> grad, hess\n\nmodel = lgb.LGBMRegressor(\n    n_estimators=<span class=\"y\">3000</span>,\n    learning_rate=<span class=\"y\">0.03</span>,\n    num_leaves=<span class=\"y\">63</span>,          <span class=\"c\"># primary complexity control (not max_depth)</span>\n    min_child_samples=<span class=\"y\">30</span>,  <span class=\"c\"># min samples per leaf \u2014 key overfitting guard</span>\n    subsample=<span class=\"y\">0.8</span>,\n    colsample_bytree=<span class=\"y\">0.8</span>,\n    reg_alpha=<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>,\n    reg_lambda=<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>,\n    monotone_constraints=[-<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>, -<span class=\"y\">1</span>],   <span class=\"c\"># per feature: -1/0/+1</span>\n    random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># With custom loss function</span>\nmodel_custom = lgb.LGBMRegressor(objective=mape_loss, ...)\ncallbacks = [lgb.early_stopping(<span class=\"y\">50</span>), lgb.log_evaluation(<span class=\"y\">200</span>)]\nmodel_custom.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)], callbacks=callbacks)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 06. CATBOOST \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-cat\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>CatBoost \u2014 ordered boosting</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 what ordered boosting prevents</span>\n    <p>In standard gradient boosting, the residual for example i is computed using a model trained on all data including i itself. This is a form of target leakage \u2014 example i's own label influenced the model used to compute i's residual, making the residual signal slightly optimistic.<br><br>\n    Ordered boosting assigns a random temporal order to all training examples. The residual for example i is computed using only a model trained on examples that appear before i in this ordering. No example ever influences its own residual computation. This is more expensive (different model per example in theory; approximated in practice) but produces better-calibrated residuals, especially on small datasets.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why this matters for categorical encoding</span>\n    <p>Target encoding (replacing a categorical feature value with the mean target for that value) is notorious for leakage: computing the mean target for category C using all rows including the current row means the current row's label leaked into its own feature. Ordered target statistics in CatBoost compute the target statistic for row i using only the rows that come before i \u2014 the same ordered principle. This is why CatBoost can handle raw categoricals without preprocessing and without leakage, while other frameworks' naive target encoding leaks.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 07. PRODUCTION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-prod\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Production concerns \u2014 imbalance, monotone, custom loss</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Handling class imbalance in tree-based models</span>\n    <p>Three approaches with different trade-offs:<br>\n    <strong>scale_pos_weight (XGBoost) / class_weight (LightGBM, sklearn):</strong> upweight minority class gradient contributions. Fast, no synthetic data. Affects calibration \u2014 predicted probabilities will be inflated for the minority class.<br>\n    <strong>Threshold adjustment:</strong> train on raw data, shift decision threshold using the precision-recall curve to hit your desired recall/precision operating point. Preserves calibration.<br>\n    <strong>SMOTE:</strong> creates synthetic minority examples. Works when the minority class truly needs more examples, not just more weight. Avoid if the minority class is rare due to genuine rarity in the world (fraud) \u2014 synthetic examples may not reflect reality.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Monotone constraints \u2014 when and why</span>\n    <p>Force the model to be monotonically increasing (+1) or decreasing (\u22121) in a specified feature. The model is constrained so that increasing the feature value can only increase (or only decrease) the prediction, regardless of other feature values. Critical for:<br>\n    \u2014 <strong>Load forecasting:</strong> demand should not decrease as temperature increases past 35\u00b0C (AC load is monotone with temperature in summer)<br>\n    \u2014 <strong>Pricing models:</strong> higher quality \u2192 higher price, always<br>\n    \u2014 <strong>Risk/credit models:</strong> more debt \u2192 more risk, always<br>\n    Without constraints, a model may learn non-monotone relationships from noise in the data that violate domain knowledge and create nonsensical predictions in production.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Custom MAPE loss for XGBoost (gradient + Hessian required)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">xgb_mape_loss</span>(y_pred, dtrain):\n    y_true = dtrain.get_label()\n    grad = (y_pred - y_true) / (y_true**<span class=\"y\">2</span> + <span class=\"y\">1e-8</span>)\n    hess = <span class=\"y\">1</span> / (y_true**<span class=\"y\">2</span> + <span class=\"y\">1e-8</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> grad, hess\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">xgb_mape_eval</span>(y_pred, dtrain):\n    y_true = dtrain.get_label()\n    mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / (y_true + <span class=\"y\">1e-8</span>))) * <span class=\"y\">100</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> (<span class=\"g\">'mape'</span>, mape)   <span class=\"c\"># lower is better</span>\n\nmodel_xgb = xgb.train(\n    params={<span class=\"g\">'learning_rate'</span>: <span class=\"y\">0.05</span>, <span class=\"g\">'max_depth'</span>: <span class=\"y\">6</span>},\n    dtrain=xgb.DMatrix(X_train, label=y_train),\n    num_boost_round=<span class=\"y\">2000</span>,\n    obj=xgb_mape_loss,         <span class=\"c\"># custom loss</span>\n    feval=xgb_mape_eval,       <span class=\"c\"># custom eval metric</span>\n    evals=[(dval, <span class=\"g\">'val'</span>)],\n    early_stopping_rounds=<span class=\"y\">50</span>\n)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Imbalance: threshold selection using precision-recall curve</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> precision_recall_curve\nprec, rec, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_val, y_prob_val)\n<span class=\"c\"># Find threshold that gives recall \u2265 0.9 with best precision</span>\nmask = rec >= <span class=\"y\">0.9</span>\nbest_thresh = thresholds[mask][prec[mask].argmax()]\ny_pred = (y_prob_val >= best_thresh).astype(<span class=\"y\">int</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 08. FEATURE IMPORTANCE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-fi\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Feature Importance &amp; Interpretability</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 four types and what they measure</span>\n    <p><strong>Split importance:</strong> number of times a feature is used to split a node across all trees. Biased toward high-cardinality features (more possible thresholds = more splits). Cheapest to compute. Least reliable.<br><br>\n    <strong>Gain importance:</strong> average loss reduction per split for each feature. Better than split count \u2014 a feature used rarely but always yielding large gains ranks appropriately. Still biased toward high-cardinality.<br><br>\n    <strong>Permutation importance:</strong> measure score on validation set, shuffle feature j, measure score again. Difference = importance of feature j. Model-agnostic, reliable, uses actual validation performance. Expensive (n_features \u00d7 n_repeats model evaluations).<br><br>\n    <strong>SHAP values:</strong> from cooperative game theory (Shapley values). Distribute prediction credit fairly across features, accounting for all possible feature orderings. Additive: \u03a3 SHAP values = prediction \u2212 base value. Shows direction (positive or negative contribution) and handles feature interactions correctly. The correct tool for stakeholder explanations.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">High-cardinality features inflate split-based importance</span>\n    <p>A feature with 10,000 unique values has 9,999 possible split points. The tree algorithm naturally finds more splits to use it on, inflating its split importance even if it's genuinely less informative than a binary feature. In electricity load forecasting: \"minute of day\" (96 values) will appear more important than \"is_holiday\" (2 values) by split count alone, even if is_holiday has a larger actual effect. Always verify with permutation importance or SHAP before telling stakeholders which features matter.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> shap\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.inspection <span class=\"k\">import</span> permutation_importance\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pandas <span class=\"k\">as</span> pd\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Built-in importance (gain-based is better than split-based)</span>\nlgb_imp = pd.DataFrame({\n    <span class=\"g\">'feature'</span>: X.columns,\n    <span class=\"g\">'gain'</span>: model.feature_importances_   <span class=\"c\"># gain-based by default in LightGBM</span>\n}).sort_values(<span class=\"g\">'gain'</span>, ascending=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Permutation importance \u2014 most reliable, use on validation set</span>\nperm = permutation_importance(\n    model, X_val, y_val,\n    n_repeats=<span class=\"y\">15</span>,           <span class=\"c\"># more repeats = more stable estimate</span>\n    scoring=<span class=\"g\">'neg_mean_absolute_error'</span>,\n    random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>\n)\nperm_df = pd.DataFrame({\n    <span class=\"g\">'feature'</span>: X.columns,\n    <span class=\"g\">'importance'</span>: perm.importances_mean,\n    <span class=\"g\">'std'</span>: perm.importances_std\n}).sort_values(<span class=\"g\">'importance'</span>, ascending=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># SHAP \u2014 best for explanation; shows direction and interactions</span>\nexplainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model)     <span class=\"c\"># fast tree-specific explainer</span>\nshap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_val)\n\nshap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_val)    <span class=\"c\"># global: feature vs impact, coloured by value</span>\nshap.force_plot(explainer.expected_value,\n    shap_values[<span class=\"y\">0</span>], X_val.iloc[<span class=\"y\">0</span>])       <span class=\"c\"># explain one prediction</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 Q&A \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"tree-qa\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why does bagging reduce variance? Give the mathematical argument.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">For n independent random variables each with variance \u03c3\u00b2, their mean has variance \u03c3\u00b2/n. Bootstrap-sampled trees are not independent \u2014 they share training data. Let \u03c1 be the average pairwise correlation between tree predictions. Then Var(ensemble) = \u03c1\u03c3\u00b2 + (1\u2212\u03c1)\u03c3\u00b2/n. As n\u2192\u221e, the (1\u2212\u03c1)\u03c3\u00b2/n term vanishes, leaving \u03c1\u03c3\u00b2. The variance floor is determined by how correlated the trees are. This is why feature subsampling (\u221ad features per split) is essential \u2014 it forces each tree to find different features to split on, reducing \u03c1. More trees reduce the second term, but lower \u03c1 reduces the irreducible floor. Bias stays roughly unchanged because each tree is individually a low-bias model (fully grown). The ensemble preserves low bias while dramatically reducing variance through decorrelation.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>How does XGBoost use the Hessian? Why does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">XGBoost uses a second-order Taylor expansion of the loss at each boosting step: L(y, F+h) \u2248 L + g\u00b7h + \u00bdH\u00b7h\u00b2, where g = \u2202L/\u2202F (gradient) and H = \u2202\u00b2L/\u2202F\u00b2 (Hessian). The Hessian is curvature information \u2014 how fast the gradient is changing. This allows solving analytically for the optimal leaf weight: w* = \u2212\u03a3G/(\u03a3H + \u03bb). The gain score for a split also uses Hessians. Why it matters: first-order methods (vanilla GBM) can overshoot because they don't know how curved the loss surface is. The Hessian acts like a local step-size controller \u2014 where the loss curves sharply, steps are smaller; where it's flat, steps are larger. This gives faster, more accurate convergence per tree and is why XGBoost often needs fewer trees than standard GBM to reach the same performance.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Random Forest vs XGBoost \u2014 when does each win?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Random Forest wins when: data is noisy or has outliers (bagging is naturally robust), dataset is small (&lt;10K rows, boosting overfits more easily), you want a quick reliable baseline without tuning, or training speed matters more than last-1% accuracy. XGBoost wins when: data is clean and large, features have complex interactions, you have time to tune and validate properly, or you're in a competition context. The most reliable practical rule: fit RF first as a baseline in 5 minutes. If XGBoost with early stopping doesn't improve it by a meaningful margin on your validation set, the RF's simplicity and robustness wins. Boosting's advantage over RF increases with dataset size \u2014 on 1M rows, LightGBM is almost always better; on 5K rows, RF is often safer.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What are monotone constraints and when do you use them?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Monotone constraints force the model's prediction to be monotonically increasing (+1) or decreasing (\u22121) in a specified feature, holding all other features constant. Implemented at split time \u2014 the algorithm only considers splits that maintain the monotone relationship. Use when domain knowledge guarantees a directional relationship that the model might violate due to noise: electricity demand and temperature in summer (increasing), credit risk and debt-to-income ratio (increasing), demand and price (decreasing). Without constraints, tree models can learn local non-monotone relationships from training noise that produce absurd predictions at deployment time \u2014 e.g., predicting lower load at higher temperature for a narrow temperature range because that happened to be true in one year of training data. Constraints make models more robust and explainable to stakeholders.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>SHAP vs permutation importance \u2014 which do you use and when?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Permutation importance: shuffle feature j on the validation set, measure performance drop. Tells you how much overall model performance depends on feature j. Fast, reliable, model-agnostic. Use for feature selection decisions. Limitation: doesn't account for feature interactions \u2014 if A and B are correlated, shuffling A still leaves B intact, so importance of A is underestimated. SHAP: computes each feature's contribution to each individual prediction using Shapley values. Additive \u2014 contributions sum to prediction minus baseline. Shows direction (positive or negative) and magnitude per prediction. Handles interactions by averaging over feature orderings. Use for stakeholder explanations (\"why did the model predict this load?\"), debugging individual predictions, and understanding how features interact. SHAP is more expensive but the right tool for anything requiring explanation beyond aggregate importance.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>How do you tune a gradient boosting model? What order?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Fix learning_rate=0.05 and n_estimators=2000 with early_stopping_rounds=50 \u2014 let early stopping find the right number of trees. Then tune in this order of impact: (1) max_depth or num_leaves \u2014 primary complexity control. XGBoost: try 4,6,8. LightGBM: try 31,63,127. (2) min_child_weight (XGBoost) or min_child_samples (LightGBM) \u2014 minimum samples per leaf. Raise to reduce overfitting on small datasets. (3) subsample and colsample_bytree \u2014 row and column subsampling. Usually 0.7-0.9. Introduces randomness like RF, reduces correlation between trees. (4) reg_alpha and reg_lambda \u2014 L1 and L2 penalties on leaf weights. Usually modest (0.01-1.0). (5) Only after all above: lower learning_rate to 0.01 and let n_estimators grow accordingly. Never tune learning_rate first \u2014 it interacts with everything else. Use Optuna or RandomizedSearchCV, not GridSearch \u2014 the space is too large for exhaustive search.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_clustering": "<main>\n  <h1>Clustering</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">KMeans</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">EM algorithm, choosing K, limitations</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">DBSCAN</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Density-based, arbitrary shapes, outlier detection</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Hierarchical Clustering</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Dendrograms, linkage methods, when to use</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Evaluation</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Silhouette score, Davies-Bouldin, elbow \u2014 and their limits</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>KMeans' three fatal assumptions:</strong> spherical clusters (elongated or crescent shapes are split wrong), equal-size clusters (a large cluster \"donates\" points to small ones to balance centroid distances), and no outliers (extreme values pull centroids, distorting all cluster positions). When any of these fail \u2014 use DBSCAN or GMM instead.</li>\n    <li><strong>KMeans convergence guarantee without optimality guarantee:</strong> the EM algorithm (assign \u2192 update centroids \u2192 repeat) is guaranteed to converge because WCSS never increases. It is not guaranteed to find the global minimum \u2014 it finds a local one. Always run multiple times with different initialisations (n_init=10+) and keep the best WCSS. K-means++ initialisation reduces sensitivity to starting position.</li>\n    <li><strong>DBSCAN's varying density failure:</strong> a single \u03b5 parameter cannot handle clusters of very different densities \u2014 \u03b5 too small fragments dense clusters, \u03b5 too large merges loose ones. HDBSCAN solves this by finding the right density threshold per cluster automatically. For anomaly detection: DBSCAN labels outliers as \u22121 explicitly, which is useful, but Isolation Forest or LOF often outperform it specifically for anomaly detection tasks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Silhouette score vs elbow method:</strong> the elbow method plots WCSS vs K and looks for a kink \u2014 highly subjective, often no clear elbow exists. Silhouette score s(i) = (b\u2212a)/max(a,b) where a = avg distance to same cluster, b = avg distance to nearest different cluster. Range [\u22121,1], higher is better. More principled than the elbow. But neither tells you if the clusters are meaningful for your business problem \u2014 always validate clusters by examining human-interpretable characteristics of each group.</li>\n    <li><strong>Scale before clustering:</strong> both KMeans and DBSCAN use distance metrics. A feature with range [0,10000] completely dominates distances over one with range [0,1]. Always StandardScale or RobustScale before clustering. PCA before high-dimensional clustering (both KMeans and DBSCAN degrade above ~20 dimensions \u2014 the curse of dimensionality applies to distance-based methods).</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. KMEANS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clust-kmeans\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>KMeans</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 objective and algorithm</span>\n    <p>KMeans minimises the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS):<br>\n    <strong>J = \u03a3\u2096 \u03a3\u1d62\u2208C\u2096 ||x\u1d62 \u2212 \u03bc\u2096||\u00b2</strong><br><br>\n    Algorithm (Lloyd's EM approach):<br>\n    1. Initialise K centroids (K-means++ for smarter initialisation \u2014 reduces sensitivity to random seed)<br>\n    2. Assignment step: assign each point to its nearest centroid<br>\n    3. Update step: recompute each centroid as the mean of its assigned points<br>\n    4. Repeat steps 2-3 until assignments stop changing<br><br>\n    Guaranteed to converge (WCSS never increases), not guaranteed to find the global minimum. Always run multiple times with different initialisations (n_init=10 or more) and keep the best result.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">KMeans' three fatal assumptions \u2014 violated constantly in real data</span>\n    <p><strong>1. Spherical clusters:</strong> KMeans uses Euclidean distance from centroid. Elongated, crescent-shaped, or non-convex clusters are split incorrectly \u2014 a cluster shaped like a C is split into two spheres.<br><br>\n    <strong>2. Equal cluster sizes:</strong> if one cluster has 10,000 points and another has 100, KMeans may \"steal\" points from the large cluster to balance centroid distance calculations.<br><br>\n    <strong>3. No outliers:</strong> extreme values pull centroids toward them, distorting cluster positions. KMeans assigns every point to a cluster \u2014 there's no concept of noise or outlier.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.cluster <span class=\"k\">import</span> KMeans\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> silhouette_score\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Scale first \u2014 KMeans uses Euclidean distance</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> StandardScaler\nX_scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Choose K: compare silhouette scores (more rigorous than elbow)</span>\nscores = {}\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> k <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">12</span>):\n    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init=<span class=\"g\">'k-means++'</span>, n_init=<span class=\"y\">15</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\n    labels = km.fit_predict(X_scaled)\n    scores[k] = silhouette_score(X_scaled, labels)   <span class=\"c\"># [-1,1], higher=better</span>\n\nbest_k = max(scores, key=scores.get)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Best K by silhouette: {best_k} (score: {scores[best_k]:.3f})\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Final model</span>\nkm_final = KMeans(n_clusters=best_k, init=<span class=\"g\">'k-means++'</span>, n_init=<span class=\"y\">20</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nlabels = km_final.fit_predict(X_scaled)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Cluster sizes: {np.bincount(labels)}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># check for very unequal clusters</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. DBSCAN \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clust-dbscan\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>DBSCAN</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 density-based clustering</span>\n    <p>DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) groups points by density rather than distance to centroids. Two parameters:<br>\n    <strong>\u03b5 (eps):</strong> neighbourhood radius.<br>\n    <strong>min_samples:</strong> minimum points within \u03b5 to form a \"dense region.\"<br><br>\n    Three types of points:<br>\n    <strong>Core point:</strong> has \u2265 min_samples neighbours within radius \u03b5. Forms the dense heart of a cluster.<br>\n    <strong>Border point:</strong> within \u03b5 of a core point but itself has fewer than min_samples neighbours.<br>\n    <strong>Noise point:</strong> not within \u03b5 of any core point. Labelled \u22121. These are outliers.<br><br>\n    Clusters are formed by expanding from core points to all density-reachable points. No K to specify. Finds arbitrary shapes. Labels outliers explicitly.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 city density from satellite</span>\n    <p>Looking at a map from space: dense urban areas (many buildings within a radius) form city cores. The buildings expand out to suburbs. Isolated farmhouses in between are not part of any city \u2014 they're noise.<br><br>\n    DBSCAN: dense core points expand their cluster to include neighbours. Isolated points that aren't near enough to any core are noise. The shape of the cluster is determined by what's dense, not by a circle drawn around a centroid.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">DBSCAN fails with varying density</span>\n    <p>If clusters have different densities \u2014 one cluster is very tight, another is loose \u2014 a single \u03b5 either merges the loose clusters together (\u03b5 too large) or fragments the tight cluster (\u03b5 too small). HDBSCAN (hierarchical DBSCAN) solves this by automatically finding the right density threshold per cluster. For anomaly detection specifically: Isolation Forest or LOF often outperform DBSCAN because they're designed for detecting anomalies in datasets where \"normal\" points can have varying density.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.cluster <span class=\"k\">import</span> DBSCAN\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Choosing eps: use k-distance graph</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># For each point, compute distance to its min_samples-th nearest neighbour</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Plot sorted distances \u2014 \"elbow\" suggests a good eps</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.neighbors <span class=\"k\">import</span> NearestNeighbors\nnbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=<span class=\"y\">5</span>).fit(X_scaled)\ndistances, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(X_scaled)\ndistances = np.sort(distances[:, -<span class=\"y\">1</span>])   <span class=\"c\"># 5th nearest neighbour distance</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Plot distances and look for the \"knee\" \u2014 that's your eps</span>\n\ndb = DBSCAN(eps=<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>, min_samples=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\nlabels = db.fit_predict(X_scaled)\n\nn_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (<span class=\"y\">1</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> -<span class=\"y\">1</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> labels <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"y\">0</span>)\nn_noise    = (labels == -<span class=\"y\">1</span>).sum()\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Clusters: {n_clusters}, Noise points: {n_noise} ({n_noise/len(labels)*100:.1f}%)\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. HIERARCHICAL \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clust-hier\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Hierarchical Clustering</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 agglomerative approach</span>\n    <p>Agglomerative hierarchical clustering starts with n clusters (one per point) and merges the two closest clusters at each step until one cluster remains. The full history of merges is stored in a <strong>dendrogram</strong> \u2014 cutting the dendrogram at any height gives a K-cluster solution. No K needed upfront \u2014 explore the hierarchy and cut where it makes sense.<br><br>\n    <strong>Linkage criteria</strong> determine how \"distance between clusters\" is computed:<br>\n    <strong>Single:</strong> minimum distance between any two points (one in each cluster). Prone to chaining \u2014 creates elongated chains. <strong>Complete:</strong> maximum distance. Creates compact spherical clusters. <strong>Average:</strong> average of all pairwise distances. Balance. <strong>Ward:</strong> minimises the total within-cluster variance after merging. Creates equal-size clusters. Most commonly used in practice.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> scipy.cluster.hierarchy <span class=\"k\">import</span> dendrogram, linkage, fcluster\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> matplotlib.pyplot <span class=\"k\">as</span> plt\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Compute linkage matrix \u2014 Ward minimises within-cluster variance</span>\nZ = linkage(X_scaled, method=<span class=\"g\">'ward'</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Plot dendrogram to choose K visually</span>\nplt.figure(figsize=(<span class=\"y\">10</span>, <span class=\"y\">6</span>))\ndendrogram(Z, truncate_mode=<span class=\"g\">'lastp'</span>, p=<span class=\"y\">12</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># show last 12 merges</span>\nplt.title(<span class=\"g\">'Dendrogram \u2014 cut at the longest vertical line with no horizontal crossing'</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Cut to get K clusters</span>\nK = <span class=\"y\">4</span>\nlabels = fcluster(Z, K, criterion=<span class=\"g\">'maxclust'</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. EVALUATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"clust-eval\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Evaluating Clusters</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 internal metrics (no ground truth needed)</span>\n    <p><strong>Silhouette coefficient:</strong> for each point i, compute a = mean distance to points in same cluster, b = mean distance to points in nearest different cluster. s(i) = (b \u2212 a) / max(a, b). Range: [\u22121, 1]. Higher = point is well-matched to its cluster and poorly matched to others. Average across all points is the overall silhouette score.<br><br>\n    <strong>Davies-Bouldin index:</strong> average ratio of within-cluster scatter to between-cluster separation. Lower = better. Less intuitive than silhouette.<br><br>\n    <strong>Elbow method:</strong> plot WCSS (inertia) vs K. The \"elbow\" where WCSS drops sharply and then flattens is suggested K. Highly subjective \u2014 the elbow often doesn't exist clearly.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Cluster evaluation metrics don't tell you if clusters are useful</span>\n    <p>A high silhouette score means clusters are geometrically well-separated. It does not mean the clusters are meaningful for your business purpose. Always validate clusters by examining what differentiates each cluster in human-interpretable terms. Customer segmentation: do different clusters have meaningfully different purchase behaviour? If cluster A and cluster B buy the same things at the same frequency, the clustering is geometrically valid but practically useless.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"clust-qa\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>How does KMeans work and what are its limitations?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">KMeans minimises within-cluster sum of squares: J = \u03a3\u2096 \u03a3\u1d62\u2208C\u2096 ||x\u1d62 \u2212 \u03bc\u2096||\u00b2. Algorithm: (1) Initialise K centroids (K-means++ for smarter init). (2) Assign each point to nearest centroid. (3) Recompute centroids as means of assigned points. (4) Repeat until convergence. Guaranteed to converge, not to global minimum \u2014 run multiple times. Limitations: (1) Assumes spherical, roughly equal-sized clusters \u2014 elongated or non-convex shapes are incorrectly split. (2) Every point is assigned to a cluster \u2014 no concept of outlier or noise. (3) K must be specified upfront. (4) Sensitive to initialisation and outliers \u2014 outliers pull centroids. Scale before using \u2014 Euclidean distance is scale-sensitive.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>KMeans vs DBSCAN \u2014 when do you choose each?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">KMeans: use when clusters are roughly spherical and equal-sized, you know K (or can determine it via silhouette), and the dataset is large (KMeans is O(n\u00b7K\u00b7d) per iteration, very scalable). DBSCAN: use when cluster shapes are arbitrary (crescent, ring), you don't know K, you want outliers explicitly labelled rather than forced into clusters, or you're doing anomaly detection. DBSCAN fails when clusters have very different densities \u2014 a single \u03b5 can't capture both. In that case: HDBSCAN, which automatically finds the right density per cluster. For very high-dimensional data: both KMeans and DBSCAN degrade (curse of dimensionality for DBSCAN's distance calculations). Reduce dimensions first with PCA or UMAP before clustering.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_dimred": "<main>\n  <h1>Dimensionality Reduction</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">PCA</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Eigenvectors, explained variance, when it applies</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">t-SNE</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Non-linear, local structure, visualisation only</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">UMAP</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Faster than t-SNE, preserves global structure</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">When to use each</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Linear vs non-linear, exploration vs pipeline</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>PCA maximises variance, not information:</strong> PCA finds the orthogonal directions of maximum variance via eigendecomposition of the covariance matrix. Variance explained by component i = \u03bb\u1d62/\u03a3\u03bb. But maximum variance \u2260 maximum information for your task \u2014 a feature that varies a lot may be noise, and a feature with small variance may be the most predictive. PCA is unsupervised and task-agnostic. For supervised tasks, consider LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) which maximises class separation instead.</li>\n    <li><strong>Scale before PCA, always:</strong> PCA maximises variance. A feature in [0,10000] has 10,000\u00d7 more variance than one in [0,1] by scale alone. Without scaling, PC1 is dominated by the large-scale feature regardless of its information content. StandardScale first.</li>\n    <li><strong>PCA loses interpretability:</strong> PC1 might be 0.4\u00d7temperature + 0.3\u00d7humidity \u2212 0.2\u00d7wind_speed + ... \u2014 no human-interpretable meaning. If you need to explain which features matter to a stakeholder, use feature selection (SelectKBest, Lasso) rather than PCA. PCA is for dimensionality reduction when interpretability doesn't matter.</li>\n    <li><strong>Three things t-SNE cannot tell you:</strong> (1) global distances between clusters are meaningless \u2014 two clusters far apart in the 2D plot may be close in the original space; (2) cluster sizes are meaningless \u2014 t-SNE adjusts density for visual clarity, not to reflect true proportions; (3) results are stochastic \u2014 different random seeds produce completely different layouts. Report the seed. t-SNE is visualisation only \u2014 never use it as a preprocessing step for a ML pipeline.</li>\n    <li><strong>UMAP vs t-SNE:</strong> UMAP is faster (O(n log n) vs t-SNE's O(n\u00b2)), preserves more global structure alongside local, is deterministic by default, and can transform new points without refitting the whole embedding. Use UMAP when you need reproducibility or have large n (&gt;50K points). UMAP can also be used as a preprocessing step for clustering \u2014 t-SNE cannot.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. PCA \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"dr-pca\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>PCA \u2014 Principal Component Analysis</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 eigenvectors of the covariance matrix</span>\n    <p>PCA finds orthogonal directions in feature space that maximise variance. Formally, it computes the eigendecomposition of the covariance matrix:<br>\n    <strong>Cov(X) = X\u1d40X / (n\u22121) = V\u039bV\u1d40</strong><br><br>\n    where V = matrix of eigenvectors (principal components) and \u039b = diagonal matrix of eigenvalues. The eigenvalues represent the variance along each component. Components are sorted by eigenvalue in descending order \u2014 the first PC captures the most variance.<br><br>\n    <strong>Variance explained by component i = \u03bb\u1d62 / \u03a3\u1d62\u03bb\u1d62</strong><br><br>\n    Project data onto the top k components: Z = XV_k. This gives a k-dimensional representation that preserves the maximum possible variance from the original d-dimensional space.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 finding the best angle to photograph a 3D object</span>\n    <p>You have a 3D sculpture and want one photograph that captures it best. The best angle is the one where the sculpture appears the widest \u2014 where it spans the most visual space. That is the first principal component \u2014 the direction of maximum spread. The second best photo angle, perpendicular to the first, is the second component. PCA is finding the sequence of camera angles that preserve the most information about the 3D shape in 2D projections.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">PCA loses interpretability \u2014 components are not features</span>\n    <p>PCA components are linear combinations of all original features with no semantic meaning. PC1 might be \"0.4\u00d7temperature + 0.3\u00d7humidity \u2212 0.2\u00d7wind_speed + ...\" \u2014 there's no human-interpretable label. If you need to explain your model to stakeholders, PCA preprocessing makes that harder. For dimensionality reduction with interpretability: use feature selection (SelectKBest, Lasso) instead of PCA. For visualisation only: t-SNE or UMAP are better.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.decomposition <span class=\"k\">import</span> PCA\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.preprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> StandardScaler\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.pipeline <span class=\"k\">import</span> Pipeline\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Always scale first \u2014 PCA is variance-based</span>\npca_pipe = Pipeline([\n    (<span class=\"g\">'scaler'</span>, StandardScaler()),\n    (<span class=\"g\">'pca'</span>,    PCA(n_components=<span class=\"y\">0.95</span>))   <span class=\"c\"># keep 95% of variance</span>\n])\n\nX_reduced = pca_pipe.fit_transform(X_train)\nn_components = pca_pipe.named_steps[<span class=\"g\">'pca'</span>].n_components_\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Kept {n_components} components from {X_train.shape[1]} features\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Inspect explained variance per component</span>\npca = PCA().fit(StandardScaler().fit_transform(X_train))\nexplained_var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_\ncumulative    = np.cumsum(explained_var)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># How many components needed for 95% variance?</span>\nn95 = np.argmax(cumulative >= <span class=\"y\">0.95</span>) + <span class=\"y\">1</span>\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Components for 95% variance: {n95}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Top 5 components: {explained_var[:5].round(3)}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. T-SNE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"dr-tsne\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>t-SNE</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 non-linear dimensionality reduction for visualisation</span>\n    <p>t-SNE (t-distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding) maps high-dimensional data to 2D or 3D for visualisation by preserving local neighbourhood structure. For each point, it models the probability distribution of picking a neighbour (using a Gaussian kernel in high-d space). In the low-d map, it uses a t-distribution (heavier tails, prevents crowding). It minimises the KL divergence between the high-d and low-d distributions via gradient descent.<br><br>\n    <strong>Key parameter: perplexity</strong> (roughly = number of effective nearest neighbours, typically 5-50). High perplexity = more global structure. Low perplexity = more local structure.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Three things t-SNE cannot tell you</span>\n    <p><strong>1. Global distances are meaningless.</strong> Two clusters far apart in the t-SNE plot may be close in the original space, or far \u2014 you cannot tell. Only proximity within the local neighbourhood is preserved.<br><br>\n    <strong>2. Cluster sizes are meaningless.</strong> t-SNE adjusts the density of clusters for visual clarity. A large-looking cluster is not necessarily larger than a small one.<br><br>\n    <strong>3. Different runs give different layouts.</strong> t-SNE is stochastic. With a different random seed, clusters might appear in completely different positions. Always report the random seed. Use UMAP instead if you need reproducibility by default.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. UMAP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"dr-umap\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>UMAP</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 faster, more principled non-linear reduction</span>\n    <p>UMAP (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection) constructs a high-dimensional graph where edges represent nearby points (using fuzzy set theory), then finds a low-dimensional layout that preserves this graph structure. Key differences from t-SNE: (1) Faster \u2014 O(n log n) vs t-SNE's O(n\u00b2). (2) Preserves more global structure alongside local. (3) Deterministic by default. (4) Can transform new points without recomputing the entire embedding \u2014 t-SNE cannot. (5) Can be used as a preprocessing step for ML pipelines \u2014 not just visualisation.<br><br>\n    <strong>n_neighbors</strong>: number of local neighbours. Low (5-15) \u2192 local structure, more fragmented. High (50-200) \u2192 global structure, smoother.<br>\n    <strong>min_dist</strong>: minimum distance between points in embedding. Lower = tighter clusters.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> umap\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.manifold <span class=\"k\">import</span> TSNE\n\n<span class=\"c\"># t-SNE: use after PCA for large datasets (PCA reduces dims, t-SNE handles the rest)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.decomposition <span class=\"k\">import</span> PCA\n\nX_pca = PCA(n_components=<span class=\"y\">50</span>).fit_transform(StandardScaler().fit_transform(X))\ntsne = TSNE(n_components=<span class=\"y\">2</span>, perplexity=<span class=\"y\">30</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>, n_iter=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>)\nX_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(X_pca)   <span class=\"c\"># 2D coordinates for visualisation only</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># UMAP: faster, can transform new points, more consistent</span>\nreducer = umap.UMAP(n_neighbors=<span class=\"y\">15</span>, min_dist=<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>, n_components=<span class=\"y\">2</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nreducer.fit(X_train)\nX_train_umap = reducer.transform(X_train)\nX_test_umap  = reducer.transform(X_test)   <span class=\"c\"># can transform new points \u2014 t-SNE cannot</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. WHEN TO USE \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"dr-which\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>When to Use Each</h2>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th></th><th>PCA</th><th>t-SNE</th><th>UMAP</th></tr>\n    <tr><td>Type</td><td>Linear</td><td>Non-linear</td><td>Non-linear</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Preserves</td><td>Global variance (linear)</td><td>Local neighbourhood</td><td>Local + some global</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Speed</td><td>Fast O(nd\u00b2)</td><td>Slow O(n\u00b2)</td><td>Fast O(n log n)</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Deterministic?</td><td>Yes</td><td>No (stochastic)</td><td>Yes (with seed)</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>New points?</td><td>Yes \u2014 transform()</td><td>No \u2014 refit needed</td><td>Yes \u2014 transform()</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Use in ML pipeline?</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td>Yes (cautiously)</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Use for visualisation?</td><td>Basic only</td><td>Yes \u2014 best for clusters</td><td>Yes \u2014 better than t-SNE for large n</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"dr-qa\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is PCA and what does it compute mathematically?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">PCA finds orthogonal directions in feature space that maximise variance, computed via eigendecomposition of the covariance matrix Cov(X) = X\u1d40X/(n\u22121) = V\u039bV\u1d40. Eigenvectors V are the principal components (directions); eigenvalues \u039b are the variances along those directions. Components are sorted by eigenvalue in descending order. Variance explained by component i = \u03bb\u1d62/\u03a3\u03bb\u1d62. Projecting data onto the top k eigenvectors gives the k-dimensional representation preserving maximum variance. Two requirements: scale the data first (PCA is variance-based \u2014 large-scale features dominate). And: PCA is linear \u2014 it finds the best linear subspace. Cannot capture non-linear structure (curved manifolds).</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What can you not conclude from a t-SNE plot?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Three things: (1) Global distances are meaningless \u2014 clusters far apart in the 2D plot may be close in the original space. t-SNE preserves local neighbourhood structure, not global distances. (2) Cluster sizes are meaningless \u2014 t-SNE adjusts point density for visual clarity, not to reflect true cluster sizes. (3) Stability \u2014 different random seeds give different layouts. The same data can look completely different. You can conclude: which points are nearest neighbours to each other (local structure), and roughly which groups of points cluster together. You cannot use t-SNE as a preprocessing step for a machine learning pipeline \u2014 it can't transform new points without refitting the entire embedding.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "ml_evaluation": "<main>\n  <h1>Model Evaluation</h1>\n\n  <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Classification Metrics</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Confusion matrix, precision, recall, F1</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">AUC-ROC vs AUC-PR</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">When each applies \u2014 imbalanced classes</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Regression Metrics</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">MAE, RMSE, R\u00b2, MAPE, sMAPE</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Calibration</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Reliability diagrams, Brier score, Platt scaling</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Business Metrics vs ML Metrics</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The gap that kills production models</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n  <h2>Revision</h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Accuracy is useless for imbalanced classes:</strong> 99% negative class \u2192 always predict negative \u2192 99% accuracy, 0% recall, undefined precision. Accuracy is only meaningful when classes are balanced. Always report F1, AUC-ROC, and confusion matrix for classification tasks with any imbalance.</li>\n    <li><strong>AUC-ROC vs AUC-PR:</strong> AUC-ROC = probability a random positive scores higher than a random negative. FPR = FP/(FP+TN) \u2014 with 99% negative class, TN is enormous, so FPR stays low even with many false positives in absolute terms. AUC-ROC looks good while the model is practically useless. AUC-PR directly measures precision at each recall level \u2014 it penalises false positives immediately. Rule: positive class &lt;10% \u2192 use AUC-PR, not AUC-ROC.</li>\n    <li><strong>Precision vs recall trade-off \u2014 the operational decision:</strong> precision = of all positive predictions, what fraction is correct. Recall = of all actual positives, what fraction did we catch. They trade off via the classification threshold. Spam filter: high precision (don't mark legitimate email as spam). Cancer screening: high recall (don't miss a real cancer \u2014 false alarms are acceptable). Tune the threshold on the validation set using the precision-recall curve, not the default 0.5.</li>\n    <li><strong>Calibration \u2014 probability estimates vs reality:</strong> a model predicting P=0.8 for 100 cases should have ~80 of them actually positive. Random Forest overestimates confidence \u2014 probabilities cluster near 0 and 1. Use calibration_curve() to diagnose. Fix with Platt scaling (CalibratedClassifierCV with method='sigmoid') or isotonic regression. Calibration matters when probabilities feed downstream decisions: expected value calculations, risk scores, cost-sensitive thresholds.</li>\n    <li><strong>MAPE and near-zero demand:</strong> in electricity demand forecasting, overnight feeder demand can drop toward zero. A single interval with actual=0.5 MW, predicted=1.0 MW gives MAPE=100% \u2014 one outlier destroys the metric. Use weighted MAPE (weight = actual demand), sMAPE, or document a minimum threshold below which intervals are excluded from the calculation.</li>\n    <li><strong>Business metric \u2260 ML metric:</strong> AUC-ROC for a fraud model treats a missed \u00a310 fraud and a missed \u00a310,000 fraud identically. MAPE for load forecasting treats a 10% error at 2am (low demand, negligible grid impact) the same as a 10% error at 6pm peak (potential grid instability). Always design evaluation metrics that reflect actual costs and consequences, not just statistical elegance.</li>\n  </ol>\n</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 01. CLASSIFICATION METRICS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-clf\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Classification Metrics</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the confusion matrix and derived metrics</span>\n    <p>For binary classification with positive class = 1:<br>\n    <strong>TP</strong> (True Positive): predicted 1, actually 1.<br>\n    <strong>FP</strong> (False Positive): predicted 1, actually 0. Type I error.<br>\n    <strong>FN</strong> (False Negative): predicted 0, actually 1. Type II error.<br>\n    <strong>TN</strong> (True Negative): predicted 0, actually 0.<br><br>\n    Derived metrics:<br>\n    <strong>Precision = TP / (TP + FP)</strong> \u2014 of all predicted positives, fraction correct. Penalises false alarms.<br>\n    <strong>Recall (Sensitivity) = TP / (TP + FN)</strong> \u2014 of all actual positives, fraction captured. Penalises missed detections.<br>\n    <strong>Specificity = TN / (TN + FP)</strong> \u2014 of all actual negatives, fraction correctly identified.<br>\n    <strong>F1 = 2\u00b7Precision\u00b7Recall / (Precision + Recall)</strong> \u2014 harmonic mean. Useful single metric when both P and R matter.<br>\n    <strong>F\u03b2 = (1+\u03b2\u00b2)\u00b7P\u00b7R / (\u03b2\u00b2\u00b7P + R)</strong> \u2014 generalised F: \u03b2 &gt; 1 weights recall more, \u03b2 &lt; 1 weights precision more.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">When to optimise precision vs recall</span>\n    <p><strong>Optimise precision</strong> when false positives are costly: spam filter (legitimate email incorrectly marked spam is very bad \u2014 you miss important messages), recommender system (irrelevant recommendations hurt user experience).<br><br>\n    <strong>Optimise recall</strong> when false negatives are costly: cancer screening (missing a real cancer is far worse than a false alarm that leads to more tests), fraud detection (missing \u00a310,000 fraud is worse than flagging a legitimate \u00a350 transaction for review), equipment failure prediction (missing a failure that causes downtime is worse than unnecessary maintenance).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Accuracy is useless for imbalanced classes \u2014 always report F1 and AUC</span>\n    <p>With 99% negative class, a model that always predicts negative achieves 99% accuracy. It has caught zero actual positives. Recall = 0. F1 = 0. Precision is undefined. Accuracy is a meaningful metric only when classes are balanced. For any problem with class imbalance, report: F1 (or F\u03b2), AUC-ROC, AUC-PR, and the confusion matrix. Never report accuracy alone.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 02. AUC-ROC vs AUC-PR \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-auc\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>AUC-ROC vs AUC-PR</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 what each curve measures</span>\n    <p><strong>ROC curve:</strong> plots True Positive Rate (Recall) vs False Positive Rate at every possible threshold. FPR = FP/(FP+TN).<br>\n    <strong>AUC-ROC</strong> = area under ROC curve = probability that the model assigns a higher score to a random positive than a random negative. Range [0.5, 1.0] for a useful model. Threshold-free \u2014 measures ranking quality across all thresholds.<br><br>\n    <strong>Precision-Recall curve:</strong> plots Precision vs Recall at every threshold.<br>\n    <strong>AUC-PR</strong> (Average Precision) = area under PR curve. Particularly informative when the positive class is rare.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">AUC-ROC is misleading for severe class imbalance</span>\n    <p>With 1% positive class (99% negative), there are 99\u00d7 as many true negatives as positives. FPR = FP/(FP+TN). Even with many false positives in absolute terms, FPR stays low because TN is enormous. The ROC curve looks good while the model is practically useless for identifying positives.<br><br>\n    AUC-PR is more honest: if your model gets many false positives, precision drops immediately and the PR curve collapses. A random classifier on 1% positive data has AUC-ROC \u2248 0.5 and AUC-PR \u2248 0.01. A real model is compared against this baseline. Use AUC-PR when positive class &lt; 10%.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> (roc_auc_score, average_precision_score,\n    RocCurveDisplay, PrecisionRecallDisplay, classification_report)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Always get probabilities, not binary predictions</span>\ny_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, <span class=\"y\">1</span>]\n\nauc_roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)\nauc_pr  = average_precision_score(y_test, y_prob)  <span class=\"c\"># area under PR curve</span>\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"AUC-ROC: {auc_roc:.4f}  AUC-PR: {auc_pr:.4f}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Full classification report: precision/recall/F1 per class</span>\nprint(classification_report(y_test, model.predict(X_test)))\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Threshold selection: find threshold that meets a business requirement</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> precision_recall_curve\nprec, rec, thresh = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_prob)\n<span class=\"c\"># Requirement: recall \u2265 0.90 with maximum precision</span>\nmask = rec >= <span class=\"y\">0.90</span>\nbest_thresh = thresh[mask][prec[mask].argmax()]\ny_pred_tuned = (y_prob >= best_thresh).astype(<span class=\"y\">int</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Threshold {best_thresh:.3f}: precision={prec[mask].max():.3f}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 03. REGRESSION METRICS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-reg\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Regression Metrics</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 the five metrics you need</span>\n    <p><strong>MAE = mean(|y \u2212 \u0177|).</strong> Same units as target. Robust to outliers (linear penalty). Interpretable: \"on average, predictions are off by X units.\" Non-differentiable at 0 \u2014 cannot be used as a loss function directly with gradient descent without modification.<br><br>\n    <strong>RMSE = \u221amean((y \u2212 \u0177)\u00b2).</strong> Same units as target. Penalises large errors more than MAE. Differentiable \u2014 can be used as loss function. More sensitive to outliers.<br><br>\n    <strong>R\u00b2 = 1 \u2212 SS_res/SS_tot.</strong> Proportion of variance in y explained by the model. R\u00b2=1 is perfect. R\u00b2=0 means the model is no better than predicting the mean. R\u00b2 can be negative (model worse than mean predictor). Not bounded below.<br><br>\n    <strong>MAPE = mean(|y\u2212\u0177|/|y|) \u00d7 100.</strong> Scale-independent percentage error. Useful for comparing across different scales or periods. Breaks when y \u2248 0.<br><br>\n    <strong>sMAPE = mean(2|y\u2212\u0177|/(|y|+|\u0177|)) \u00d7 100.</strong> Symmetric version. Bounded [0, 200%]. Handles near-zero targets more gracefully than MAPE.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">MAPE in electricity demand forecasting \u2014 where it breaks</span>\n    <p>In overnight low-load periods, feeder demand can drop to near zero. One 0.5 MW actual, 1.0 MW predicted: MAPE = 100%. That one interval can dominate the entire day's metric. Standard approach for load forecasting: use weighted MAPE (weight = actual demand, so low-demand intervals contribute proportionally less), or exclude intervals below a documented threshold (e.g., &lt; 5% of peak demand), or report both MAE and MAPE and be explicit about near-zero exclusions. sMAPE is safer if you don't want to exclude intervals.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\nmae  = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)\nrmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))\nr2   = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># MAPE \u2014 exclude near-zero values</span>\nthreshold = <span class=\"y\">0.1</span> * y_test.max()   <span class=\"c\"># e.g., exclude if < 10% of peak</span>\nmask = y_test > threshold\nmape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test[mask] - y_pred[mask]) / y_test[mask])) * <span class=\"y\">100</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># sMAPE \u2014 safer near zero</span>\nsmape = np.mean(<span class=\"y\">2</span> * np.abs(y_test - y_pred) / (np.abs(y_test) + np.abs(y_pred))) * <span class=\"y\">100</span>\n\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"MAE: {mae:.2f} | RMSE: {rmse:.2f} | R\u00b2: {r2:.4f}\"</span>)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"MAPE (excl. near-zero): {mape:.2f}% | sMAPE: {smape:.2f}%\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 04. CALIBRATION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-calib\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Calibration</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 do predicted probabilities match actual frequencies?</span>\n    <p>A model is well-calibrated if predicted probability p matches the empirical frequency of positive outcomes. If the model says P(y=1) = 0.8 for 100 instances, approximately 80 of them should actually be positive.<br><br>\n    <strong>Reliability diagram (calibration curve):</strong> bin predictions by predicted probability (0-10%, 10-20%, etc.), plot actual positive rate per bin vs predicted probability. Perfect calibration = diagonal line.<br><br>\n    <strong>Brier score = mean((y \u2212 P(y=1|x))\u00b2)</strong>. Lower is better. Combines calibration and discrimination. Range [0, 1]. A perfectly calibrated model with perfect discrimination scores 0.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Random Forest probabilities are poorly calibrated \u2014 overconfident</span>\n    <p>Random Forest uses vote proportions as probabilities. Predictions cluster near 0 and 1 because tree votes are discrete. A RF that outputs P=0.9 may be correct only 70% of the time for those instances. Logistic regression is usually well-calibrated by construction (it directly maximises the likelihood of the labels). When calibrated probabilities matter (risk scores, expected value calculations), apply post-hoc calibration: Platt scaling (fits a logistic regression on top of model scores) or isotonic regression (more flexible, more data needed).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.calibration <span class=\"k\">import</span> calibration_curve, CalibratedClassifierCV\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.metrics <span class=\"k\">import</span> brier_score_loss\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> matplotlib.pyplot <span class=\"k\">as</span> plt\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Check calibration</span>\nfrac_pos, mean_pred = calibration_curve(y_test, y_prob, n_bins=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\nplt.plot(mean_pred, frac_pos, <span class=\"g\">'s-'</span>, label=<span class=\"g\">'Model'</span>)\nplt.plot([<span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>], [<span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">1</span>], <span class=\"g\">'k--'</span>, label=<span class=\"g\">'Perfect calibration'</span>)\n<span class=\"c\"># If model line is below diagonal \u2192 overconfident. Above \u2192 underconfident.</span>\n\nbrier = brier_score_loss(y_test, y_prob)\nprint(f<span class=\"g\">\"Brier score: {brier:.4f}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># lower is better</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Calibrate a Random Forest (Platt scaling)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> sklearn.ensemble <span class=\"k\">import</span> RandomForestClassifier\nrf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=<span class=\"y\">200</span>, random_state=<span class=\"y\">42</span>)\nrf_calibrated = CalibratedClassifierCV(rf, method=<span class=\"g\">'sigmoid'</span>, cv=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># Platt</span>\nrf_calibrated.fit(X_train, y_train)\ny_prob_cal = rf_calibrated.predict_proba(X_test)[:, <span class=\"y\">1</span>]</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 05. BUSINESS VS ML METRICS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-business\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Business Metrics vs ML Metrics</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The most important thing about evaluation</span>\n    <p>ML metrics (AUC-ROC, F1, RMSE) are proxies for business value. They are useful, standardised, and comparable. They are not the actual goal. A model with 0.95 AUC-ROC that misses the specific type of fraud your business is exposed to is worse than a model with 0.85 AUC-ROC that catches them. Always define what a correct prediction is worth and what a wrong prediction costs \u2014 then check if your ML metric is actually correlated with that value.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Three common metric-business objective mismatches</span>\n    <p><strong>1. Fraud detection optimised on AUC-ROC:</strong> AUC-ROC treats a missed \u00a31 fraud the same as a missed \u00a310,000 fraud. A model that catches many small frauds but misses large ones has high AUC-ROC but terrible business performance. Use value-weighted metrics: weight false negatives by fraud amount.<br><br>\n    <strong>2. Demand forecasting optimised on MAPE:</strong> MAPE weights low-demand intervals (which have minimal grid impact) the same as peak demand intervals (which can cause grid instability). Use weighted MAPE or hour-specific MAPE where weights = impact of errors at each time slot.<br><br>\n    <strong>3. Recommendation system optimised on CTR:</strong> click-through rate measures engagement, not satisfaction. A recommendation of a controversial or alarming article may get high CTR but low user satisfaction. Business metric: long-term retention, not immediate CTR.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"eval-qa\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\">\n    <h3>Say your answer out loud before revealing</h3>\n    <button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button>\n  </div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When would you use AUC-PR instead of AUC-ROC?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">When the positive class is severely underrepresented (less than 10% of data). With severe imbalance, FPR = FP/(FP+TN) stays small even with many false positives in absolute terms, because TN is enormous. The ROC curve looks good while the model performs poorly on finding actual positives. AUC-PR is more sensitive to false positives in imbalanced settings: if your model produces many FPs, precision drops immediately and the PR curve collapses. A random classifier on 1% positive class data has AUC-ROC \u2248 0.5 but AUC-PR \u2248 0.01 \u2014 the PR metric correctly shows how far a model has to go. For fraud detection, anomaly detection, rare disease diagnosis: always report AUC-PR alongside AUC-ROC.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is model calibration and why does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Calibration is whether the model's predicted probabilities match actual empirical frequencies. If the model says P(y=1)=0.8 for 100 instances, 80 of them should actually be positive. A calibrated model allows you to use predicted probabilities directly in decision making: expected value calculations, risk scores, threshold selection. Poorly calibrated models can rank correctly (high AUC-ROC) while having completely wrong probability estimates. Random Forest is typically overconfident \u2014 probabilities cluster near 0 and 1, under-representing the true uncertainty. Logistic regression is usually well-calibrated. Fix with post-hoc calibration: Platt scaling (fits sigmoid on top of model scores) for models with monotone scores; isotonic regression for more flexible calibration with more data.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>RMSE vs MAE \u2014 when does each give a better view of model performance?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">MAE is the average absolute error \u2014 every error is penalised proportionally to its size. It gives a clean, interpretable number (on average, predictions are off by X units). Robust to outliers \u2014 one massive error doesn't dominate. RMSE squares errors, giving extra weight to large errors. Use RMSE when large errors are disproportionately costly (an error of 10 is more than 2\u00d7 worse than an error of 5), or when you're using MSE as a loss function and want the evaluation metric to match. Use MAE when errors are roughly equally costly regardless of size, or when the data has outliers you don't want to inflate the metric. In practice: report both. If RMSE is much larger than MAE, large errors are common \u2014 investigate why.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
});